[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hello everyone! I am Grandmaster Leinier Dominguez and I want to welcome you to my first Chessable course where I will be presenting a repertoire for Black against 1.d4 based on the Semi-Tarrasch Defense.     The Semi-Tarrasch Defense is played against the Queen's Gambit, one of the most popular ways for White to open the game. It comes about after the moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Nf3  c5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.cxd5  Nxd5  . It’s a very classical way of playing because it challenges the center immediately with the move ...c7-c5.   It has been played from the early 20th century by great players from the past like Schlechter, Alekhine, Euwe and many others. Then it became quite popular at the top level in the sixties, with players like Tal employing it quite often and with success, especially the more classical form with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  .  Then in 1969 two famous games @@StartBracket@@Spassky-Petrosian and Polugaevsky-Tal@@EndBracket@@ inflicted a huge blow on the Defense which made it disappear almost completely from high-level practice for several decades!  It wasn’t until 2013 that Kramnik started to demonstrate some new ways for Black and after several other strong players @@StartBracket@@myself included@@EndBracket@@ also joined the Black cause, the modern theory of the Semi-Tarrasch started to develop and it became established as a super solid and reliable weapon.  There are a few reasons why I chose this opening for the course:  First of all because having played it myself and analyzed it a great deal, I feel that I am in a good position to equip you with all that knowledge and experience.Secondly, I like the solidity of this opening, we will usually get a sound position where we know very well what we are doing in terms of plans and ideas in the middle game and where eventually we might have good chances to counterattack.Finally, I also like that, in a way, it’s a very universal line for black, meaning you can easily base your repertoire against 1.c4 and 1.Nf3 on this opening.  So it’s a line where in general you can avoid a lot of theory and make your preparation a bit easier because you choose move orders against 1.c4 and 1.Nf3 that fit quite well with this opening line.  Now let's have a look at the board and see some move order details and I will also explain what the course does and what it doesn't cover. }
1. d4
{ This is obviously the subject of this course but I wanted to say a brief word about the moves 1.c4 and 1.Nf3. As I mentioned earlier, having the Semi-Tarrasch in mind against 1.d4, we have relatively simple ways to build our repertoire against these moves as well.   Against  1.c4  ,  1...e6  would be a good way to respond here, now a transposition to the lines we cover in the course is very likely. White can deviate and choose a sideline but those are normally not that difficult to counter. Now for instance, after  2.Nc3  d5  3.d4  Nf6  transposes back to main lines of our course.   And  2.g3  d5  3.Bg2  Nf6  will most likely transpose to the Catalan Opening.   Obviously, there are many ways to play against  1.Nf3  but I would recommend playing  1...d5  followed by ...Nf6 and ...e6 when again, a transposition to normal Queen's Gambit positions is likely if white goes for c4 and d4. }
1... d5
{ This is the main move order that I will present.   Another possible move order is  1...Nf6!?  when we have the Semi-Tarrasch in mind, especially for those of you who already have the Nimzoindian in your repertoires.  2.c4  e6  The reason 1...Nf6 is an interesting move order is that in this position many white players prefer to avoid the Nimzoindian and play 3.Nf3 or 3.g3, which take away some options from white, such as the dangerous 7.Rb1 line.  3.Nc3   3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  c5  Transposing to our course main position  Bb4  And play transposes to the Nimzo-Indian Defense.   3...d5  transposes to 1...d5 and to our main line in the course anyway. }
2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ 3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  This is again the main continuation here by far, it transposes to our main line with 3.Nc3. White has some alternatives but we will not be covering them in this course. The main alternative is the Catalan and then 4.Bg5 and 4.e3 are considered sidelines in the Queen's Gambit and should be covered in a different course.   4.g3  The Catalan is of course one of the main systems for White here but it will not be part of our study in this course, I think it deserves separate study and there is indeed some material already on Chessable on this subject. }
3... Nf6
{ Now white has 3 main continuations, although we cover some other unusual moves as well in the course. }
4. Nf3
{ 4.cxd5  is very critical and popular, leading to sharp positions after  4...Nxd5  5.e4   5.Nf3  c5  transposes.  Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  White has several options here, 7.Rb1 being the most challenging one but overall I am satisfied with the recommendations that I give in the course.   4.Bg5  is in fact the most employed move in this position. Here play is a bit different than in the typical Semi-Tarrasch. }
4... c5
{ And we arrive at the starting position of the Semi-Tarrasch.  From here on, we will study all possible continuations and I will be giving concrete recommendations against each line, but more than that, since this opening is quite rich, we will encounter many different types of pawn structures, like isolated queen's pawn, hanging pawns, central pawn majority and so forth.  In each one of those structures, I will try to give you explanations and tips that go beyond the opening phase, I will point out general middle game concepts and techniques characteristic of each one of those positions.  My goal with this approach is to give you a solid understanding of the main positional foundations of this opening, in such a way that it will be easier for you to fix or update any concrete line that needs it in the future.  By the end of our study, you should have a very sound and comprehensive weapon against the Queen's Gambit and more importantly, one that will be possible for you to understand quite well and immediately start implementing it in practice.  In general, I believe that a major opening like the Semi-Tarrasch will never be refuted, so you will have a lifetime weapon in this course. Finally, I also hope that you will enjoy the time working on this course and that you will find it useful and instructive. Now let's jump right into it! }
