1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center. We are technically speaking not yet in Semi-Tarrasch territory but we are getting very close to it. After the move  5.cxd5  we intend to recapture  5...Nxd5  . }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Now we make clear that we will play the Semi-Tarrasch and not the Classical Tarrasch Defense, where Black takes back with the pawn on d5 and then plays actively with an isolated pawn in the center.  Our choice is very different in nature, we will give up a little space in the center but in return, we get a very solid position with no pawn weaknesses and good strategic prospects in the long run. }
6. e3
{ This is the second most employed move in this position.   It is not as ambitious as  6.e4  , White simply aims for normal development and is willing to play positions with an IQP or even hanging pawns. }
6... cxd4 7. exd4 { 7.Nxd5?!  Qxd5  makes little sense for White. } 7... Nxc3
{ Black has a few options here but I decided to recommend this line which is extremely sound and offers nice practical chances as well. }
8. bxc3 Qc7
{ We play against the hanging pawns. In these positions, White usually needs to rely on the dynamic factors and play aggressively most of the time.  Positionally Black is doing well as the pawns can be potentially weak, so again, trades tend to favor us but we need to be alert regarding White's attacking ideas.  Usually, the best squares for our pieces are:bishop on b7 @@StartBracket@@after ...b7-b6@@EndBracket@@,knight on d7 and eventually f6,bishop on d6 where it will exert pressure on h2 and make possible the simplifying maneuver Bd6-f4 in many lines. }
9. Bd2
{ This is the most obvious move and it's considered to be the main line, but there are some alternatives worth studying. }
9... Nd7 10. Bd3
{ By far the most popular move here.   10.Ng5  Nf6  11.Qf3  Bd6  12.Bd3  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppqn1ppp/4p3/8/3P4/2P2N2/P2B1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bd3  Bd6  11.Ng5  Nf6  12.Qf3  . }
10... Bd6 11. O-O { This looks like the best move for White. } 11... b6
{ The most precise move order. It's important to get the bishop to b7 before castle here.   11...O-O  seems logical too but after  12.Qe2!  White is able to create more problems, for example,  12...b6   12...Nf6  13.Ne5  is also promising for White.  13.Qe4  This is the point, and even though White is not really taking the rook, after  13...g6  14.Qh4↑  White has greater chances of successfully developing a kingside attack. }
12. Ng5
{ From this point on, it's hard to say what is White's main line.  It seems to me that this move is very much in line with the demands of the position and that's why I will treat it as our main line. Other moves have been played but somehow they seem more harmless. }
12... Bb7
{ 12...Bxh2+  13.Kh1  Bf4  Also seems promising for White after  14.Qh5  g6  15.Qf3  Bxg5  16.Bxg5  Bb7  17.Qg4↑  With good compensation for the pawn.   12...Nf6  Might be playable too but I don't like the fact that after  13.f4  h6  14.Nf3  White get some attacking chances and the capture on f4 just doesn't work:  14...Bxf4?  15.Bxf4  Qxf4  16.Ne5  Qe3+  17.Kh1+-  and White is winning. }
13. f4
{ The most consistent, now White has Nf3-e5 in case of ...h6.   13.Re1  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/p1qn1ppp/1p1bp3/8/3P4/2PB1N2/P2B1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Re1  Bb7  13.Ng5  . }
13... h6 14. Nf3 { Once again the logical choice. } 14... O-O 15. Ne5 Rad8 16.
Bc2 f5
{ A strong positional idea that is important to remember, this is why Black is not afraid of the Ne5-f4 construction.  Now the idea is ...Nf6, controlling the e4-square. After that, Black can choose the best moment to eliminate the white knight. }
17. Bb3 Bd5 18. Qe2
{ 18.c4?  Bxe5!  ∓  And Black is nearly winning, is an important tactical point. }
18... Bxb3 19. axb3 Nf6
{ The position is probably around equal but I prefer Black's chances in practice, due to the possibility of taking on e5 and installing an eternal knight on e4. }
