1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center, we are not yet technically speaking in Semi-Tarrasch territory. }
5. e3
{ This is the 2nd major continuation in this position apart from  5.cxd5  . It is very rich in transpositions as we could get now different openings depending on how Black plays. }
5... a6
{ After some consideration, I decided to pick this move as our main here.  The alternatives are all viable, of course, but I feel that this one gives White fewer options @@StartBracket@@which is always nice@@EndBracket@@ and at the same time, the lines are relatively easy to play and remember as Black.  We are agreeing to play with an isolated pawn now, but I believe a very decent version.  The move ...a6 is very useful in these positions as it takes control of the b5-square and also gives the a7-square for our bishop, just in case. }
6. a3
{ 6.Be2?!  dxc4  7.Bxc4  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3?!  dxc4  7.Bxc4  . }
6... dxc4
{ Now we play in Queen's Gambit Accepted style. This specific version though is very comfortable for Black. }
7. Bxc4 b5 8. Ba2 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7
{ Black's play is quite natural and easy here. We would like to play ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Qc7 and so on.  Let's look at a couple of possible continuations. }
10. Qe2 Bd6 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. b4 Ncd7
{ The best continuation. The knight will have nice prospects on d7  @@StartBracket@@it could go to b6-c4 or to e5@@EndBracket@@ but most importantly, it's good for Black to keep the c3-knight on the board as it hampers the action of White's pieces, especially the b2-bishop and c1-rook.   13...Nce4?!  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Bb2⩲  And once the c3-knight gets traded, White's position becomes better. }
14. Bb2 Rc8 15. Rac1 Qb8
{ The position is about equal, Black has no problems at all. } *

