[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.cxd5: 5.e4 − Alternatives to 7.Rb1 − 7.a3 #1/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5
{ This is one of the main lines and White's idea is to meet  4...exd5  with  5.Bg5  with the famous Carlsbad structure which slightly favors White.   The options gained by White with this move order are mainly connected to the position reached after  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  and here White has a few options other than  7.Nf3  .  Most notably the line with  7.Rb1  which I argue is one of the most dangerous systems in the whole course.   White can also transpose back to 4.Nf3 lines in a couple of instances, for example, after  4...Nxd5  White could play  5.Nf3  here when Black would play  5...c5  . }
4... Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5
{ This is the starting position of another big line in the Semi-Tarrasch. I believe this particular one, especially the move  7.Rb1  here, is the most dangerous for Black.  Black does not get to trade bishops with ...cxd4 and ...Bb4+ which means that White's space advantage and central pawn majority could play a more important role as there are more pieces on the board, but, as I am going to demonstrate, Black's position is perfectly sound and very playable at all levels. }
7. a3
{ This is also played quite often, although not as much as  7.Rb1  . The idea is similar, to stop Black from playing ...cxd4 and ...Bb4+. }
7... cxd4
{ I like this very concrete approach here, it seems like a natural way of meeting the relatively soft a2-a3.   An interesting alternative is  7...g6!?  leading to Grunfeld type of positions, but I prefer the text. }
8. cxd4 e5
{ Immediately forcing matters in the center.   Now White can close the center with  9.d5  , protect it with  9.Nf3  or play a more open position with  9.dxe5  . }
9. Nf3 exd4 10. Qxd4 { The most challenging. Alternatives are quite harmless. }
10... Be7
{ This is very precise here I believe. We don't want to take on d4 as that would give White some Nd4-b5 options later on. }
11. Bb5+ { 11.Bc4  O-O  Black has easy development and a good position. } 11...
Nc6 12. Qxd8+ Bxd8
{ We always recapture with the bishop so that we are able to castle normally. }
13. O-O O-O
{ White was not able to obtain much, Black's play still seems rather easy to me here, very much like in the previous variations.  Now we will probably follow with ...Re8 and then get our bishops out, for instance: }
14. Be3 Re8 15. Rfd1 a6 16. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Again we accept the weakening of our queenside structure, but in return, we get the bishop pair and the e4-pawn is still a little weak.   The position is approximately equal, here is a sample line:  17.Rac1  c5  18.Rxc5  Bb7  19.Nd2  Bxe4  20.Nxe4  Rxe4=  And the game is heading to a draw. }
*

