8. Bb5+
{ This is the 2nd most employed move here, it is quite a solid move but it is not considered to be dangerous for Black. }
8... Bd7 { Now White can choose between a few options. } 9. Bd3
{ Probably the most logical. Now we don't waste time defending b7 but rather we try to develop quickly, counterattacking in the center. }
9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Nc6 11. Be2
{ Was tried by Mamedyarov against Kramnik in 2018 but it is a bit suspicious to move the bishop so many times and indeed Black gets a good position after }
11... Rc8 12. Nf3 Qa5+ 13. Bd2 Bb4 14. Rb2 Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2
{ We are still following the aforementioned game, and here I like } 15... b6
{ A familiar concept in these positions, Black waits for castles before trading queens, just so that White's king doesn't get so easily to e3. }
16. d5 exd5 17. exd5 Qxd2+ 18. Rxd2 Na5
{ Black has a typically good endgame, in fact, I already prefer Black's position here because the central pawn is not going anywhere, Black's king is well-positioned in the center and the c-file is under Black's control. }
