[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Other 4th moves: 4.Bg5 #1/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Let's quickly take a look at the alternatives to  4.cxd5  and  4.Nf3  . } 4.
Bg5
{ This move is actually the most employed in this position, but it is also true that modern theory considers  4.Nf3  and especially  4.cxd5  to be more challenging for Black.  So we can not really call  4.Bg5  a sideline as it is a very principal option here but it has lost popularity over the aforementioned alternatives in practice in the last few years. }
4... Be7
{ We enter the classical Queen's Gambit Declined territory but these lines with Bg5 instead of Bf4 are actually not especially dangerous for Black. }
5. Nf3 h6
{ This is considered to be slightly more precise than the immediate  5...O-O  .  Now White has 2 main options and we get very different types of positions in each case. }
6. Bh4 dxc4
{ There are several options here but I like this one for its simplicity. } 7.
e3 { 7.e4?  Nxe4!  and Black wins material, is an important point. } 7... c5 8.
Bxc4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 { The most solid, not compromising the pawn structure. } 9...
Bd7
{ Most accurate, intending ...Nc6.   Just for reference,  9...O-O  10.Qb3!?  is probably okay too but requires more precision. }
10. O-O
{ 10.Qb3  Nc6  is now quite easy for Black. If  11.Qxb7  then at the very least Black has  11...Na5  12.Qa6  Bc8  13.Qb5+  Bd7=  with a draw. }
10... Nc6
{ Again we reach a position that is very symmetrical in terms of the pawn structure. White has a very slight initiative that usually disappears after a couple of precise moves by Black. }
11. Nb3 { Played with the idea to avoid trades. } 11... O-O 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. Be2
Nd5 { A very precise way to liberate our pieces. } 14. Bg3
{ 14.Bxe7  Ncxe7=  .   14.Nxd5?!  Bxh4  Only Black can be better with the two bishops now. }
14... Nxc3 15. Rxc3 Nb4 16. Rxc8 Qxc8
{ Black comfortably equalized in the game Carlsen-Caruana, Tata Steel 2020.  The knight can always go back to d5 to solidify the position but also ...Ba4, ...Rd8 is an idea, depending on what White does. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Other 4th moves: 4.Bg5 #2/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Let's quickly take a look at the alternatives to  4.cxd5  and  4.Nf3  . } 4.
Bg5
{ This move is actually the most employed in this position, but it is also true that modern theory considers  4.Nf3  and especially  4.cxd5  to be more challenging for Black.  So we can not really call  4.Bg5  a sideline as it is a very principal option here but it has lost popularity over the aforementioned alternatives in practice in the last few years. }
4... Be7
{ We enter the classical Queen's Gambit Declined territory but these lines with Bg5 instead of Bf4 are actually not especially dangerous for Black. }
5. Nf3 h6
{ This is considered to be slightly more precise than the immediate  5...O-O  .  Now White has 2 main options and we get very different types of positions in each case. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6
{ This is also a big tabiya of the QGD but it is actually quite solid and good for Black and it has been considered to be so for several years by now.  In general Black's main idea is to take on c4 and then use either the ...c7-c5 or ...e6-e5 break to completely solve the opening problems.  There is a huge body of theory here but I will present to you what I think is vital to know when playing Black. }
7. e3
{ 7.Rc1  O-O  8.e3  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  O-O  8.Rc1  . }
7... O-O 8. Rc1
{ This is the main move order, and it makes a lot of sense, as White is waiting for Black to take on c4 to develop his bishop with tempo. }
8... c6 9. Bd3
{ White finally gives up the waiting battle, as there are not especially good useful moves. }
9... Nd7 10. O-O dxc4 11. Bxc4 c5
{ There is also  11...e5  but I prefer the text as it seems to me that Black's play is easier here. }
12. Qe2 cxd4 13. exd4
{ This is the most ambitious. White accepts to play with an isolani, with all the pros and cons that come with such a strategy.  I like Black's chances in this specific case. Our goals are pretty clear, at least in terms of piece placement: the knight will go to b6, controlling - and later, possibly occupying - the d5-square. The queen's bishop will be best placed on c6 via d7, the queen goes to e7 and the f8-rook to d8.  White needs to look for active chances on the kingside, mostly related to Bd3-Qe4-h4-h5 ideas.  All in all, in concrete terms, it seems to work for Black.   13.Nxd4  Qb6  is not a problem. }
13... Nb6 14. Bb3 Bd7 15. Ne5 Bc6
{ And Black is doing well, we are not really afraid of the capture on c6 as that structure can only be better for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 4.Nf3: 6.e4 − Alternatives to 11.Bc4"]
[Black "4.Nf3: 6.e4 − 11.Bd3 #1/9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center. We are technically speaking not yet in Semi-Tarrasch territory but we are getting very close to it. After the move  5.cxd5  we intend to recapture  5...Nxd5  . }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Now we make clear that we will play the Semi-Tarrasch and not the Classical Tarrasch Defense, where Black takes back with the pawn on d5 and then plays actively with an isolated pawn in the center.  Our choice is very different in nature, we will give up a little space in the center but in return, we get a very solid position with no pawn weaknesses and good strategic prospects in the long run. }
6. e4
{ White's most obvious and ambitious response, taking control of the center.  The position now strongly resembles the Grunfeld Defense, the main difference is that here Black has ...e7-e6 instead of ...g7-g6 and that means of course that we will develop our dark-squared bishop in a different way. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+
{ This check, with the subsequent trade of bishops, is a key element in Black's whole concept with this opening.  The trade will reduce White's potential for a kingside attack  @@StartBracket@@let's not forget that another pair of minor pieces has already been exchanged@@EndBracket@@ and also it will allow Black to move more freely with his remaining pieces. }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O
{ The starting position of the Semi-Tarrasch. White enjoys some space advantage and a central majority but Black has no weaknesses and the simplified nature of the position means that Black will not have problems finding enough good squares for his pieces.  White's main ideas are connected to the d4-d5 push, sometimes to create a strong passed pawn and sometimes answering ...exd5 with e4-e5 sacrificing a pawn but getting a nice kingside initiative in return.  Also, the full advance of the h-pawn trying to create weaknesses around the black king is on White's agenda.  Generally speaking, one of Black's main ideas is to simplify the position even further as we have a potentially very good endgame with the 2 vs 1 configuration on the queenside so trades tend to be good for us.  The black bishop is almost always best placed on b7 but when it comes to the knight, we have two options: d7 or c6. It will depend on how White is playing, of course, d7 is more solid but we will be playing ...Nc6 in some positions as well, especially when d4-d5 is under control.  It is also very important to understand that as Black we should be using prophylactic thinking quite a lot here. Often we will be making moves that are designed specifically to prevent White's ideas @@StartBracket@@especially the d4-d5 advance@@EndBracket@@. In other words, we should keep our patience. }
11. Bd3
{ An interesting choice, White immediately places his bishop on an active diagonal. }
11... Nc6
{ We take advantage of the fact that White can not really go d4-d5 so easily and we develop the knight to the most active square. }
12. e5
{ Of course,  12.d5?!  looks dubious with the king still in the center:  12...exd5  13.exd5  Re8+  and Black gets the initiative. }
12... Ne7
{ Now that White showed his hand with e4-e5, this move makes a lot of sense as it serves more than one purpose, the knight takes control of the d5-square which was weakened by White's advance but it could also go to f5 eventually, putting pressure on d4 and most importantly it is ready to move to g6 as well where it will protect the king against possible attacking attempts. }
13. h4 { 13.Ng5  doesn't bring anything to White after  13...h6  . } 13... Bd7
14. Rh3 Bc6
{ Black is doing well here as all his pieces are excellently placed and White's attempts to attack on the kingside are easily neutralized. }
15. Rg3 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Ng6
{ And we are counter-attacking against both pawns on d4 and h4. Black is much better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 4.Nf3: 6.e4 − Alternatives to 11.Bc4"]
[Black "4.Nf3: 6.e4 − 11.Bd3 #2/9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center. We are technically speaking not yet in Semi-Tarrasch territory but we are getting very close to it. After the move  5.cxd5  we intend to recapture  5...Nxd5  . }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Now we make clear that we will play the Semi-Tarrasch and not the Classical Tarrasch Defense, where Black takes back with the pawn on d5 and then plays actively with an isolated pawn in the center.  Our choice is very different in nature, we will give up a little space in the center but in return, we get a very solid position with no pawn weaknesses and good strategic prospects in the long run. }
6. e4
{ White's most obvious and ambitious response, taking control of the center.  The position now strongly resembles the Grunfeld Defense, the main difference is that here Black has ...e7-e6 instead of ...g7-g6 and that means of course that we will develop our dark-squared bishop in a different way. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+
{ This check, with the subsequent trade of bishops, is a key element in Black's whole concept with this opening.  The trade will reduce White's potential for a kingside attack  @@StartBracket@@let's not forget that another pair of minor pieces has already been exchanged@@EndBracket@@ and also it will allow Black to move more freely with his remaining pieces. }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O
{ The starting position of the Semi-Tarrasch. White enjoys some space advantage and a central majority but Black has no weaknesses and the simplified nature of the position means that Black will not have problems finding enough good squares for his pieces.  White's main ideas are connected to the d4-d5 push, sometimes to create a strong passed pawn and sometimes answering ...exd5 with e4-e5 sacrificing a pawn but getting a nice kingside initiative in return.  Also, the full advance of the h-pawn trying to create weaknesses around the black king is on White's agenda.  Generally speaking, one of Black's main ideas is to simplify the position even further as we have a potentially very good endgame with the 2 vs 1 configuration on the queenside so trades tend to be good for us.  The black bishop is almost always best placed on b7 but when it comes to the knight, we have two options: d7 or c6. It will depend on how White is playing, of course, d7 is more solid but we will be playing ...Nc6 in some positions as well, especially when d4-d5 is under control.  It is also very important to understand that as Black we should be using prophylactic thinking quite a lot here. Often we will be making moves that are designed specifically to prevent White's ideas @@StartBracket@@especially the d4-d5 advance@@EndBracket@@. In other words, we should keep our patience. }
11. Bd3
{ An interesting choice, White immediately places his bishop on an active diagonal. }
11... Nc6
{ We take advantage of the fact that White can not really go d4-d5 so easily and we develop the knight to the most active square. }
12. e5
{ Of course,  12.d5?!  looks dubious with the king still in the center:  12...exd5  13.exd5  Re8+  and Black gets the initiative. }
12... Ne7
{ Now that White showed his hand with e4-e5, this move makes a lot of sense as it serves more than one purpose, the knight takes control of the d5-square which was weakened by White's advance but it could also go to f5 eventually, putting pressure on d4 and most importantly it is ready to move to g6 as well where it will protect the king against possible attacking attempts. }
13. O-O { 13.Ng5  doesn't bring anything to White after  13...h6  . } 13... Bd7
{ A strong move as we are aiming to place our bishop on the h1-a8 diagonal where it will exert annoying pressure and the constant threat of ...Bxf3. }
14. Ng5 h6 15. Ne4 Bc6 16. Nd6 Nc8
{ And Black is doing very well as after the knight trade White's temporary initiative comes to an end and Black's heavy pieces will come into play creating a lot of problems for White, especially with the d4-pawn. }
*

