{ The starting position of the Semi-Tarrasch. White enjoys some space advantage and a central majority but Black has no weaknesses and the simplified nature of the position means that Black will not have problems finding enough good squares for his pieces.  White's main ideas are connected to the d4-d5 push, sometimes to create a strong passed pawn and sometimes answering ...exd5 with e4-e5 sacrificing a pawn but getting a nice kingside initiative in return.  Also, the full advance of the h-pawn trying to create weaknesses around the black king is on White's agenda.  Generally speaking, one of Black's main ideas is to simplify the position even further as we have a potentially very good endgame with the 2 vs 1 configuration on the queenside so trades tend to be good for us.  The black bishop is almost always best placed on b7 but when it comes to the knight, we have two options: d7 or c6. It will depend on how White is playing, of course, d7 is more solid but we will be playing ...Nc6 in some positions as well, especially when d4-d5 is under control.  It is also very important to understand that as Black we should be using prophylactic thinking quite a lot here. Often we will be making moves that are designed specifically to prevent White's ideas @@StartBracket@@especially the d4-d5 advance@@EndBracket@@. In other words, we should keep our patience. }
11. Bd3
{ An interesting choice, White immediately places his bishop on an active diagonal. }
11... Nc6
{ We take advantage of the fact that White can not really go d4-d5 so easily and we develop the knight to the most active square. }
12. Bc2
{ Now we have to be careful, the attempt to go to the endgame straight away is dubious as White can take advantage of the fact that his king is still in the center and therefore much more active!   Of course,  12.d5?!  looks dubious with the king still in the center:  12...exd5  13.exd5  Re8+  and Black gets the initiative. }
12... Qe7
{ This is very precise, we want to bring our rook to d8, putting pressure on d4 and also making possible ideas with ...e6-e5 and ...Bg4. It is also very important in this position to mention that we should wait for White to castle before we attempt to go for the queen trade.   In the endgame, it is much more desirable for White to have the king on e3 than to have it on g1! The queen trade is not favorable for Black when the white king is still in the center:  12...Qa5  13.Qxa5  Nxa5  14.Ke2!  would be a bit unpleasant for Black. }
13. O-O Rd8 14. d5
{ This move looks a little weird with the black rook on d8 and the white queen on d2 but as we said before, as Black we always have to consider this possibility as it is White's most important and dangerous idea and here it turns out to be quite sharp and concrete as well. }
14... Nb4 15. Bb3 exd5 16. exd5 Nxd5
{ Using the pin on the d-file, Black can eliminate this dangerous pawn. } 17.
Bxd5 Be6 18. Rae1 { The only move for White, creating a counter pin. } 18...
Qc5
{ Getting out of the pin, this time on the e-file and ready to take the bishop, now White's play is also totally forced. }
19. Rxe6 Rxd5 20. Rc1
{ Again the only move as otherwise, Black will take the rook on e6 and White will not have enough. }
20... Qb5
{ And another only move! Now it all ends peacefully after some further forced moves by both sides. }
21. Qe3 fxe6 22. Qxe6+ Kh8 23. Ng5
{ A nice resource to save the game. The immediate check on c8 would lose as Black would immediately block the check on d8 with the rook. }
23... Qd7 24. Nf7+ Kg8 25. Nh6+ Kh8
{ And the game ends with a draw by repetition. This was played in Mendonca-Keymer, Champions Chess Tour 2021. }
*

