{ The starting position of the Semi-Tarrasch. White enjoys some space advantage and a central majority but Black has no weaknesses and the simplified nature of the position means that Black will not have problems finding enough good squares for his pieces.  White's main ideas are connected to the d4-d5 push, sometimes to create a strong passed pawn and sometimes answering ...exd5 with e4-e5 sacrificing a pawn but getting a nice kingside initiative in return.  Also, the full advance of the h-pawn trying to create weaknesses around the black king is on White's agenda.  Generally speaking, one of Black's main ideas is to simplify the position even further as we have a potentially very good endgame with the 2 vs 1 configuration on the queenside so trades tend to be good for us.  The black bishop is almost always best placed on b7 but when it comes to the knight, we have two options: d7 or c6. It will depend on how White is playing, of course, d7 is more solid but we will be playing ...Nc6 in some positions as well, especially when d4-d5 is under control.  It is also very important to understand that as Black we should be using prophylactic thinking quite a lot here. Often we will be making moves that are designed specifically to prevent White's ideas @@StartBracket@@especially the d4-d5 advance@@EndBracket@@. In other words, we should keep our patience. }
11. Rc1
{ This move used to be the 2nd most employed in this position @@StartBracket@@after the main line  11.Bc4  @@EndBracket@@  , but it has fallen out of popularity in the last few years.   The idea is very similar to  11.Rd1  , White makes a useful move without committing the bishop and then in case of ...b7-b6 the white bishop goes directly on d3.  That said, the rook on c1 seems less dangerous for Black as it does not support the d4-d5 push.  Also, later on, Black can trade rooks on the c-file which is generally is favorable for the second player. }
11... b6 12. Bd3 Ba6
{ This more direct move is also possible and even though it looks riskier, it is not easy to find a refutation, here are some possible lines. }
13. Bxa6
{ 13.Rc3  Bxd3  14.Qxd3  Nd7  15.O-O  transposes back to the variation @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/p4ppp/bp2p3/8/3PP3/3B1N2/P2Q1PPP/2R1K2R w K - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.O-O  Bxd3  14.Qxd3  Nd7  15.Rc3  . }
13... Nxa6 14. O-O { 14.Qe2  Rc8=  . } 14... Qe7 15. Qe2
{ 15.Ne5  Rac8  and after playing ...Qb7 next we will get positions very similar to the main line with 15.Qe2. }
15... Qb7
{ The queen is very well placed here: it defends the knight, covers most of the entry squares along the c-file and also prepares exchanges with ...Rac8 and so on. }
16. Ne5 Rac8 17. Qb5 h6
{ This is very precise since the central push is not a threat at the moment, Black has time for this useful move.   I don't like  17...Nb8  for Black:  18.d5  exd5  19.exd5  Qe7  20.Rxc8  Rxc8  21.Re1↑  . }
18. Nc6 { 18.d5  Nc5=  . } 18... Qd7 19. d5 Nc5
{ Apart from attacking the e4-pawn, our knight is excellently placed on c5, it compensates well the strong white knight on c6. The position is balanced as Black can easily play around the white knight with moves like ...exd5, ...Rfe8, ...Re4, ...Rce8 and so on. }
*

