19. g4
{ With the obvious intention of playing g5 and possibly transferring the a5-rook to g5.  Now it makes perfect sense to force the queen trade so that we do not have to worry about the attack anymore.   19.Rc5  Qd8  does not bring anything to White, we are ready to trade rooks or to advance our a-pawn.   19.Qb4  Qd8  20.Ne5  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/pbq2pp1/4pn1p/R7/3PP3/3B1N1P/3Q1PP1/4R1K1 w - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Ne5  Qd8  20.Qb4  . }
19... Qc3 20. Qxc3 Rxc3 21. Ne5
{ Similar to the lines after @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/pbq2pp1/4pn1p/R7/3PP3/3B1N1P/3Q1PP1/4R1K1 w - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Ne5  Qc3?!  , but here Black is up a tempo @@StartBracket@@g2-g4 does not really help White@@EndBracket@@ and that is enough for Black to be ok in the endgame now. }
21... a6 22. f3 Rd8 23. Rb1 Nd7
{ This is a key defensive move, otherwise, Black's position becomes bad. Now we are just in time to get rid of the annoying knight on e5. }
24. Rxb7 Nxe5 { And draw is the most probable outcome. } *

