{ The starting position of the Semi-Tarrasch. White enjoys some space advantage and a central majority but Black has no weaknesses and the simplified nature of the position means that Black will not have problems finding enough good squares for his pieces.  White's main ideas are connected to the d4-d5 push, sometimes to create a strong passed pawn and sometimes answering ...exd5 with e4-e5 sacrificing a pawn but getting a nice kingside initiative in return.  Also, the full advance of the h-pawn trying to create weaknesses around the black king is on White's agenda.  Generally speaking, one of Black's main ideas is to simplify the position even further as we have a potentially very good endgame with the 2 vs 1 configuration on the queenside so trades tend to be good for us.  The black bishop is almost always best placed on b7 but when it comes to the knight, we have two options: d7 or c6. It will depend on how White is playing, of course, d7 is more solid but we will be playing ...Nc6 in some positions as well, especially when d4-d5 is under control.  It is also very important to understand that as Black we should be using prophylactic thinking quite a lot here. Often we will be making moves that are designed specifically to prevent White's ideas @@StartBracket@@especially the d4-d5 advance@@EndBracket@@. In other words, we should keep our patience. }
11. Bc4
{ This is by far the main line for White in this position. It is a bit more aggressive than the alternatives as the d4-d5 push gains in strength now, so we must keep that in mind and choose the most appropriate way of finishing development. }
11... Nd7
{ In the old days, they were playing mainly  11...Nc6  in this position but  11...Nd7  is way more solid and has been established as the modern main line.  It is actually thanks to this new concept that the whole Semi-Tarrasch was rehabilitated. Black is now in a much better position to counter d4-d5 in general. }
12. O-O { Clearly, nothing else makes sense for White here. } 12... b6 13. a4
{ As we mentioned before, this is a more positional treatment of the position from White.  The dream would be to exchange a couple of pawns on the queenside and then put pressure on the remaining black pawn and eventually collect it.  All this is of course very difficult in the real world as Black has a great deal of resources, as we will see.   This way of playing has lost popularity lately and indeed Black's play is not too difficult here if we know what we are doing! }
13... Bb7 14. Bd3
{ 14.Rfe1  Nf6  15.Bd3  just transposes to the main line @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb1n1ppp/1p2p3/8/P1BPP3/5N2/3Q1PPP/R4RK1 w - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Bd3  Nf6  15.Rfe1  . }
14... Nf6 15. Rfe1 h6
{ A solid and useful move @@StartBracket@@anticipating Ng5 ideas@@EndBracket@@ and leading to another tabiya of the whole Semi-Tarrasch. White has a big choice now. }
16. a5
{ The most logical, immediately following up with the strategic plan.   16.Qb4  Qc7  17.Rac1  Qf4  18.Qd2  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3pp1/1p2pn1p/8/P2PP3/3B1N2/3Q1PPP/R3R1K1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Qb2  Qc7  17.Rac1  Qf4  18.Qd2  . }
16... bxa5
{ The best reaction as first demonstrated by Kramnik, the main advocate of the Semi-Tarrasch on the top level. It turns out that it is better for Black to keep his a-pawn as it will be easier to defend. }
17. Rxa5 Qc7
{ Preparing ...Rfc8. As we will see in the variations, it is very difficult for White to put pressure on the a-pawn as his own central pawns require constant protection too. }
18. g4
{ This could potentially be a very strong idea for White, but here specifically it does not really work.   18.Rc1  Qd8  and White has nothing better than to come back to e1 with the rook.   18.Qa2  Rfc8  19.Rxa7  Rxa7  20.Qxa7  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pbq2pp1/4pn1p/R7/3PP3/3B1N2/3Q1PPP/4R1K1 w - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Qb4  Rfb8  19.Qa3  Rc8  20.Rxa7  Rxa7  21.Qxa7  . }
18... Nxg4 19. Rc5 Qe7 20. Qf4 Nf6 21. Rc7
{ This apparent double attack is White's idea, but the tactics work in our favor here. }
21... Qb4 22. Rb1 Qa3
{ We attack the white bishop and are just in time to save the piece. } 23. Ne5
Ba6 { Black is doing well. } *

