18. Qb4
{ 18.Rc1  Qd8  and White has nothing better than to come back to e1 with the rook.   18.Qa2  Rfc8  19.Rxa7  Rxa7  20.Qxa7  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pbq2pp1/4pn1p/R7/3PP3/3B1N2/3Q1PPP/4R1K1 w - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Qb4  Rfb8  19.Qa3  Rc8  20.Rxa7  Rxa7  21.Qxa7  . }
18... Rfb8 19. Rc5 { A less challenging move. } 19... Qf4 20. Qd2
{ White has to bail out: without any attacking chances on the kingside, he can easily be worse. }
20... Qxd2 21. Nxd2 Rd8 22. Nb3 a5
{ The simplest way, forcing the exchange of the pawns. } 23. Rxa5 Rxa5 24. Nxa5
Rxd4 25. Nxb7 Rxd3
{ Black had the most pleasant side of an equal endgame in Wojtaszek-Kramnik, Shamkir 2017. }
