{ In the old days, they were playing mainly  11...Nc6  in this position but  11...Nd7  is way more solid and has been established as the modern main line.  It is actually thanks to this new concept that the whole Semi-Tarrasch was rehabilitated. Black is now in a much better position to counter d4-d5 in general. }
12. O-O { Clearly, nothing else makes sense for White here. } 12... b6 13. Rac1
Bb7 14. d5
{ This move order was successfully used by Aronian against Kramnik a few years ago, but with precise play, Black has nothing to fear. }
14... exd5
{ This way seems more simple to me than the one played in the aforementioned game:   14...Nc5  15.Rfe1  Qf6  16.Qe3  Rac8  17.e5  Qg6  18.d6  f6  19.Nh4!  Qg4  20.g3  fxe5  21.Qxe5±  , Aronian-Kramnik, Stavanger 2017. White was significantly better and went on to win convincingly. }
15. Bxd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Rc8
{ Black is fine in these positions, although a bit of care is necessary obviously in order to deal with the d5-pawn. Here are some possible lines: }
17. d6 { 17.Rc6  Nf6⇆  . } 17... Qf6 18. Qd5 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Rd8
{ Here also the pawn is relatively easy controlled, White is able to defend it and ultimately probably exchange it for one of the queenside pawns, leading to a drawish endgame. }
20. Re1 h6
{ ...h6 is always useful in order to get rid of back rank issues, for instance, if the knight moves to c5 immediately White has d6-d7 and some tactics based on that. }
21. h3 { White also has some back rank issues, so he does the same. } 21... Nc5
22. Rd1 Qe6 23. Qxe6 Nxe6 24. Ne5 Nc5
{ Now Black is finally ready to bring the king to the center, after which the d-pawn will most likely fall. So White has to make a draw by repetition. }
25. Nc6 Rd7 26. Nb8 Rd8 27. Nc6 Rd7 { And the game logically ends in a draw. }
*

