{ The starting position of the Semi-Tarrasch. White enjoys some space advantage and a central majority but Black has no weaknesses and the simplified nature of the position means that Black will not have problems finding enough good squares for his pieces.  White's main ideas are connected to the d4-d5 push, sometimes to create a strong passed pawn and sometimes answering ...exd5 with e4-e5 sacrificing a pawn but getting a nice kingside initiative in return.  Also, the full advance of the h-pawn trying to create weaknesses around the black king is on White's agenda.  Generally speaking, one of Black's main ideas is to simplify the position even further as we have a potentially very good endgame with the 2 vs 1 configuration on the queenside so trades tend to be good for us.  The black bishop is almost always best placed on b7 but when it comes to the knight, we have two options: d7 or c6. It will depend on how White is playing, of course, d7 is more solid but we will be playing ...Nc6 in some positions as well, especially when d4-d5 is under control.  It is also very important to understand that as Black we should be using prophylactic thinking quite a lot here. Often we will be making moves that are designed specifically to prevent White's ideas @@StartBracket@@especially the d4-d5 advance@@EndBracket@@. In other words, we should keep our patience. }
11. Bc4
{ This is by far the main line for White in this position. It is a bit more aggressive than the alternatives as the d4-d5 push gains in strength now, so we must keep that in mind and choose the most appropriate way of finishing development. }
11... Nd7
{ In the old days, they were playing mainly  11...Nc6  in this position but  11...Nd7  is way more solid and has been established as the modern main line.  It is actually thanks to this new concept that the whole Semi-Tarrasch was rehabilitated. Black is now in a much better position to counter d4-d5 in general. }
12. O-O { Clearly, nothing else makes sense for White here. } 12... b6 13. Rad1
{ This is definitely the most dangerous line for Black and nowadays is the most popular.    The other major alternative consists of the pawn advance on the queenside trying to play a bit more positional.   The rest of the moves are far less common although the tricky  13.d5!?  has to be taken very seriously. }
13... Bb7 14. Rfe1 Rc8 15. Bb3
{ This is by far the most dangerous continuation here. In fact, the alternative is quite harmless as we will see. }
15... Re8
{ An important prophylactic move, Black will be well prepared in case White pushes d4-d5.   I want to mention that  15...Qf6  , trying to play similar to our main line, is dubious here as without a black rook on e8 White has the powerful  16.d5!?  exd5  17.e5  with a very strong initiative. }
16. h3
{ This is considered to be the main line. White takes control of the g4-square so that the set-up with Re3 and Qe2 can be implemented without worrying about ...Nf6-g4 ideas. }
16... Qf6
{ I want to suggest this interesting move as our main option here. The move has been rarely played but it seems to me to be no worse than the solid main line  16...Nf6  so we would also have the surprise factor on our side.  The main point of the move is to meet Re3, which is one of White's main ideas here @@StartBracket@@apart from the d4-d5 push@@EndBracket@@, with ...Qf4 which is a bit annoying for White.  In general, the nature of the position is such that Black needs to be patient and play a bit based on what White is doing. All of our pieces are well-placed @@StartBracket@@to meet the d4-d5 ideas@@EndBracket@@ and it is important not to be too hasty trying to play active and worsen our position in the process. }
17. Re3
{ I think most likely this is the move most White players will try here as it prepares Qe2 which is considered to be a good set-up for White and one of the main points of playing h2-h3.   17.Ba4  Red8  does not look especially useful for White. }
17... Qf4
{ The main point of our idea, in order to get rid of the black queen White will often need to play g2-g3 and then we will return our queen to the queenside when the weaknesses on the kingside will make it difficult for White to carry out the central break. }
18. Bc2
{ 18.e5?  is just bad  18...Bxf3  .   18.d5  Nc5  19.dxe6  fxe6⇆  Black's active pieces more than compensate for the slight weakness on e6. }
18... Nf6 19. Qe2 Ba6 { This typical motif works well here. } 20. Qxa6 Rxc2 21.
Qxa7 Nxe4 { And Black takes over. } *

