[Round "?"]
[White "4) 4.Nf3: 6.e3"]
[Black "4.Nf3: 6.e3 − 9.Qc2 #3/4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center. We are technically speaking not yet in Semi-Tarrasch territory but we are getting very close to it. After the move  5.cxd5  we intend to recapture  5...Nxd5  . }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Now we make clear that we will play the Semi-Tarrasch and not the Classical Tarrasch Defense, where Black takes back with the pawn on d5 and then plays actively with an isolated pawn in the center.  Our choice is very different in nature, we will give up a little space in the center but in return, we get a very solid position with no pawn weaknesses and good strategic prospects in the long run. }
6. e3
{ This is the second most employed move in this position.   It is not as ambitious as  6.e4  , White simply aims for normal development and is willing to play positions with an IQP or even hanging pawns. }
6... cxd4 7. exd4 { 7.Nxd5?!  Qxd5  makes little sense for White. } 7... Nxc3
{ Black has a few options here but I decided to recommend this line which is extremely sound and offers nice practical chances as well. }
8. bxc3 Qc7
{ We play against the hanging pawns. In these positions, White usually needs to rely on the dynamic factors and play aggressively most of the time.  Positionally Black is doing well as the pawns can be potentially weak, so again, trades tend to favor us but we need to be alert regarding White's attacking ideas.  Usually, the best squares for our pieces are:bishop on b7 @@StartBracket@@after ...b7-b6@@EndBracket@@,knight on d7 and eventually f6,bishop on d6 where it will exert pressure on h2 and make possible the simplifying maneuver Bd6-f4 in many lines. }
9. Qc2 Nd7 10. Bd3 b6 11. O-O
{ 11.Ng5  Bb7  12.O-O  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1qn1ppp/1p2p3/8/3P4/2PB1N2/P1Q2PPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.O-O  Bb7  12.Ng5  . }
11... Bb7 12. Ng5 Bd6 13. h3
{ This was tried in the blitz game Riazantsev-Kramnik, Berlin 2015 and now the most precise for Black is }
13... Rc8 14. Bd2 Bh2+
{ It's almost always useful for Black to include this check before playing ...Bf4. The king is worse on h1. }
15. Kh1 Bf4 16. Rac1 h6 17. Ne4 O-O
{ Black's chances are preferable. There is absolutely no initiative for White and the hanging pawns are going to suffer. }
