10... Bd6 11. O-O { This looks like the best move for White. } 11... b6
{ The most precise move order. It's important to get the bishop to b7 before castle here.   11...O-O  seems logical too but after  12.Qe2!  White is able to create more problems, for example,  12...b6   12...Nf6  13.Ne5  is also promising for White.  13.Qe4  This is the point, and even though White is not really taking the rook, after  13...g6  14.Qh4↑  White has greater chances of successfully developing a kingside attack. }
12. Re1
{ This also looks logical of course but after making the normal moves I fail to see a follow up for White that creates any kind of problem for Black. }
12... Bb7 { Other moves than  13.c4  are less dangerous, for example: } 13. h4
{ 13.h3  O-O  14.c4  transposes to  13.c4  . } 13... O-O 14. h5 h6 15. Qe2 Bf4
{ We have seen this typical move before, Black forces the bishop trade so that the dynamic factors decrease and the weak white pawns start to feel the pressure. }
16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. Bxf4 Qc6 18. f3 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Rac8
{ Was positionally clearly better for Black in the game Zherebukh-Shimanov, Pro Chess League 2018. }
