[White "5) 4.Nf3: 6.g3 (And 6.Bd2 & 6.Bg5)"]
[Black "4.Nf3: 6.Bd2 #1/4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center. We are technically speaking not yet in Semi-Tarrasch territory but we are getting very close to it. After the move  5.cxd5  we intend to recapture  5...Nxd5  . }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Now we make clear that we will play the Semi-Tarrasch and not the Classical Tarrasch Defense, where Black takes back with the pawn on d5 and then plays actively with an isolated pawn in the center.  Our choice is very different in nature, we will give up a little space in the center but in return, we get a very solid position with no pawn weaknesses and good strategic prospects in the long run. }
6. Bd2
{ This move also has some point, White prepares Rc1 and is ready to recapture with the bishop in case of a trade on c3.  That said, it feels a bit soft to create real problems for Black.   6.Nxd5?!  Qxd5  Makes little sense for White. Black immediately gets a good position. }
6... Nc6
{ Black has other ways too, like taking immediately on d4, but this seems even simpler to me. }
7. e4 Nxc3 8. Bxc3 { Just leads to simplifications and a likely draw after }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Bxd4 Bd7
{ With a totally equal endgame. Our bishop will sit nicely on the c6-square and after that our plan is to complete development by means of f7-f6 @@StartBracket@@blocking the d4-bishop’s scope@@EndBracket@@ and moving the dark-squared bishop.  There is no need to worry about our king's safety once the queens are off. In fact, our king could be very well placed in the center, after something like Bd6-Ke7 at some point. }
*

