[Round "?"]
[White "5) 4.Nf3: 6.g3 (And 6.Bd2 & 6.Bg5)"]
[Black "4.Nf3: 6.g3 #3/11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center. We are technically speaking not yet in Semi-Tarrasch territory but we are getting very close to it. After the move  5.cxd5  we intend to recapture  5...Nxd5  . }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Now we make clear that we will play the Semi-Tarrasch and not the Classical Tarrasch Defense, where Black takes back with the pawn on d5 and then plays actively with an isolated pawn in the center.  Our choice is very different in nature, we will give up a little space in the center but in return, we get a very solid position with no pawn weaknesses and good strategic prospects in the long run. }
6. g3
{ From all the sidelines White has on move 6, this one is probably the most dangerous. White prepares the fianchetto and hopes for a Catalan style pressure.   6.Nxd5?!  Qxd5  Makes little sense for White. Black immediately gets a good position. }
6... Nxc3
{ Black has some other decent alternatives but I like this way of playing here, it is very much in line with our general concept in the main lines. }
7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+
{ This is of course the point. We get to trade another set of minor pieces and obtain a very solid position. }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 b6
{ It's important to be able to get our bishop to the long diagonal, otherwise, the g2-bishop would exert very annoying pressure on the queenside. }
11. Bg2 Bb7 12. O-O O-O
{ The position looks a lot like the main lines we just studied but there are some differences.  The main one is obviously that White didn't play e2-e4 and the bishop is fianchettoed, which means that his set-up is more positionally oriented. There are no aggressive ideas for White now, like the d4-d5 break or play on the kingside.  It seems much more logical for White to try the a4-a5 plan in order to create a weak black pawn on the queenside and then attack it. This is what most of the variations we will see are pointing toward, but it seems to me that the plan is too soft and that Black has more than enough resources to get a very decent position. }
13. Rfd1 Nd7
{ Since White doesn't threaten e2-e4, we adopt the most solid set-up. Now White should most probably revert to the a2-a4 plan and play is quite similar to the 13.Rfc1 lines. }
14. a4 Rc8 15. a5 Be4 16. axb6 axb6
{ Again, White gets to trade the pawns but the resulting position is quite decent for Black. }
17. Qb2 h6 18. Ne1 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Nf6
{ The fact that all four rooks are still on the board doesn't change the evaluation much, Black dominates the c-file and has enough play to keep the balance. }
20. Nf3 Qc7 21. Rdb1 Nd5 22. Ra3
{ 22.e4  Nf6  and then e4-pawn is hard to defend. This is always the idea for Black here. }
22... Qb7 23. Rb3 Rc7
{ Preparing to double rooks on the c-file.  Black is doing well as the knight on d5 is very effective in the defense of the b-pawn.   It's worth noting that the attempt to kick the knight with  24.e4  doesn't achieve much after the familiar response  24...Nf6!  when Black is ok. }
