13... Nd7 14. a4 { Once again, this seems the most logical plan here. } 14...
Rc8 15. Rxc8 Qxc8 16. a5 h6
{ I like this way of playing as Black. We allow the queenside pawn trade because the resulting position is still very reasonable for us.  I believe that the scenario where White puts pressure and collects the b6-pawn without giving up something in return is simply unrealistic. Black will always get some counterplay in practice here as I will try to show in the lines. }
17. axb6 axb6 18. Qb2 Be4 19. Ne1 Bxg2 20. Nxg2 Qb7
{ Black has a few different ideas in this position: he can play ...Nf6 and ...Rb8 intending ...b5-b4 @@StartBracket@@let's not forget that the position is quite simplified and that the 'weakness' on b6 can become a very strong passed pawn@@EndBracket@@ or he can also play ...Rc8 and keep the knight on d7 defending b6 and ready to play moves like ...Qe4 and ...Rc2.  In general, as I mentioned before, it seems that Black is very comfortable in this position. }
