[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 4.Nf3: 5th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4.Nf3: 5.Bg5 #1/9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center, we are not yet technically speaking in Semi-Tarrasch territory. }
5. Bg5
{ A sharp move as it allows the capture on d4 giving Black a potential tempo-gaining follow up, Black is doing well here, of course, but precision is required. }
5... cxd4 6. Qxd4
{ This move has a clear drawback: it allows the black knight to develop with tempo. }
6... Nc6 7. Bxf6
{ White does well in taking the chance to at least weaken Black's structure.  The alternatives leave White simply with the worse position, which is no surprise, since play is quite sharp here and normally White should not be able to get away with too many extravagances in the opening.   7.Qh4?!  Be7↑  Would be clearly going too far for White. Black already has the initiative and plans to follow simply with ...O-O and then maybe ...h6 or ...Qa5 with a very promising position. }
7... gxf6 8. Qh4
{ This is more reasonable, now I think Black's simplest path is } 8... dxc4
{ Avoiding long castle among other things. Now the pawn structure is relatively symmetrical.  We have a slight defect in the kingside pawn structure but in return, we get the bishop pair and especially the dark-squared bishop can be potentially very strong.  We will play ...f5 and ...Bg7 almost invariably in the next few moves. }
9. Qxc4 Qb6
{ This is annoying since White can't castle long due to the loss of the f-pawn. }
10. e3 Qxb2 11. Rb1 Qa3 12. Be2 Qc5 13. Qb3
{ White tries to keep the queens in order to compensate the pawn, but Black should be doing even a bit better here after a logical sequence like }
13... f5 14. O-O Bg7 15. Nb5 O-O
{ And Black should slowly be able to get the c8-bishop out and keep some advantage. }
*

