[Round "?"]
[White "6) 4.Nf3: 5th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4.Nf3: 5.Bg5 #9/9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center, we are not yet technically speaking in Semi-Tarrasch territory. }
5. Bg5
{ A sharp move as it allows the capture on d4 giving Black a potential tempo-gaining follow up, Black is doing well here, of course, but precision is required. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5
{ This is the problem with the knight recapture. Now Black will get d5-d4 and although the position remains within the balanced zone, I believe Black's chances are at least not worse, for example: }
7. Nb3
{ 7.Ndb5?!  is dubious as after the simple  7...a6  8.Qa4  Bd7  The knight is pinned and White is in trouble.   7.Nc2  d4  8.Bxf6  gxf6  transposes back to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/5n2/3pp1B1/2PN4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bxf6  gxf6  8.Nc2  d4  . }
7... d4 8. Bxf6 gxf6 9. Nd5 Nc6 10. e4
{ Now the clearest way for Black was demonstrated by Wesley So in a rapid game. }
10... dxe3 11. fxe3 Nb4
{ It makes a lot of sense to eliminate the knight on d5, after that, only Black can be better. This was the game Mamedyarov-So, Pro Chess League 2020. }
