[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 4.Nf3: 5th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4.Nf3: 5.Bf4 #1/6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center, we are not yet technically speaking in Semi-Tarrasch territory. }
5. Bf4
{ This is a bit similar to  5.Bg5  , just a developing move, intending to recapture with a piece on d4. This move was tried by Carlsen against Aronian in a rapid game recently. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nbd7
{ Similarly to the 5.Bg5 line, it's logical for Black to aim for the ...e6-e5 push after ...cxd4, especially when there is a white bishop on f4 as well. }
7. Nf3
{ This is one way to address the ...e6-e5 threat and is in fact what Carlsen played in the aforementioned game against Aronian. }
7... Bb4 { After this natural developing move, Black is clearly in charge. } 8.
Qb3 Qa5 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 dxc4 11. Qxc4 e5
{ Followed by castles and the lead in development plus the better pawn structure give Black a significant advantage. }
