1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center, we are not yet technically speaking in Semi-Tarrasch territory. }
5. Bf4
{ This is a bit similar to  5.Bg5  , just a developing move, intending to recapture with a piece on d4. This move was tried by Carlsen against Aronian in a rapid game recently. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nbd7
{ Similarly to the 5.Bg5 line, it's logical for Black to aim for the ...e6-e5 push after ...cxd4, especially when there is a white bishop on f4 as well. }
7. Qa4
{ This is somehow the only move that doesn't leave White immediately with a worse position, which is already not a great sign for the first player. }
7... Bc5
{ Development with tempo is always nice. Black is planning to castle quickly and White is still a few moves away from finding safety for his king. }
8. cxd5 { 8.Ndb5?  e5-+  is obviously winning for Black. } 8... O-O
{ It's important that we can tactically justify this move here. } 9. Nb3
{ 9.dxe6?  Loses a piece to  9...Nb6-+  and is the main point of 8...O-O!. }
9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5
{ Again, White has some small positional triumphs @@StartBracket@@like the isolated pawn@@EndBracket@@ but Black's lead in development far outweigh this factor here.  It seems to me that White can keep the balance with some care. }
