1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center, we are not yet technically speaking in Semi-Tarrasch territory. }
5. dxc5
{ This move is a big concession as now Black's bishop develops with tempo and Black gets a very comfortable position. }
5... Bxc5
{ Now if White takes on d5 then after ...exd5 Black will generally have time to play ...Nc6 and a quick d5-d4.  White can also try to keep the tension. }
6. e3 O-O 7. a3
{ But here, unlike the somewhat similar line 5.e3 a6 6.dxc5 Bxc5 7.a3, Black doesn't need to spend time on playing ...a6 and instead simply goes }
7... dxc4 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxc4 a6 { With a very comfortable endgame. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 4.Nf3: 5th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4.Nf3: 5.e3 a6 6.dxc5 #1/6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center, we are not yet technically speaking in Semi-Tarrasch territory. }
5. e3
{ This is the 2nd major continuation in this position apart from  5.cxd5  . It is very rich in transpositions as we could get now different openings depending on how Black plays. }
5... a6
{ After some consideration, I decided to pick this move as our main here.  The alternatives are all viable, of course, but I feel that this one gives White fewer options @@StartBracket@@which is always nice@@EndBracket@@ and at the same time, the lines are relatively easy to play and remember as Black.  We are agreeing to play with an isolated pawn now, but I believe a very decent version.  The move ...a6 is very useful in these positions as it takes control of the b5-square and also gives the a7-square for our bishop, just in case. }
6. dxc5
{ This move and  6.cxd5  are the only moves after which Black's task of equalizing is not so simple.   6.Be2?!  dxc4  7.Bxc4  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  dxc4  7.Bxc4  . }
6... Bxc5 7. a3 { Intending b4 and Bb2. } 7... O-O 8. b4 Be7
{ I want to suggest this approach here. I think it's a bit better than the more employed  8...Ba7  .  Our idea is to undermine White's queenside structure with the move ...a6-a5, then White will be forced to give us some squares. }
9. Bb2
{ This move immediately allows Black to reach a very comfortable position by force. }
9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 b5 12. Be2 Bb7 13. O-O Nbd7
{ When Black has zero problems. In fact, Black's position is even slightly more pleasant to play. }
*

