9... Bxc5 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O
{ One of the typical IQP positions that we get in this line, the other main one is in @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p4n2/2pp4/3P4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  Nc6  8.O-O  Bd6  9.dxc5  Bxc5  . I believe Black has a nice version here. }
11... Qd6
{ I like this move quite a lot @@StartBracket@@we will play very similar in the main line as well@@EndBracket@@.  Black is planning ...Rad8, ...Rfe8, ...Ba7 and so on. I think this is a very efficient piece disposition here as Black can then play for the central break @@StartBracket@@...d5-d4@@EndBracket@@ and also the typical attacks on h2 with ...Bb8 and on f2 with ...Ne4 in case the white knight goes to a4.  It's worth noting that the a6-pawn, as I mentioned at the beginning, does a great job in preventing Nb5 while also creating room for the ...Ba7 maneuver. }
12. h3 Bh5 13. Na4
{ 13.Rc1  Rad8  14.Nh4  Bg6  15.Nxg6  hxg6  16.Bf3  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p3ppp/p1nq1n2/2bp3b/8/1PN1PN1P/PB2BPP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nh4  Bg6  14.Nxg6  hxg6  15.Bf3  Rad8  16.Rc1  . }
13... Ba7 14. Bxf6 gxf6
{ This might look ugly but in fact, Black will play ...Bg6 solidly protecting the kingside and the absence of the white bishop might tell later on, especially Black will have it easier playing ...d5-d4. }
15. Nd4 Bg6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Rc1 Rfe8 { Black's chances are already better. }
