{ This is by far the main continuation and as we have seen, the alternatives are not very challenging for Black.   6.Be2?!  dxc4  7.Bxc4  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3?!  dxc4  7.Bxc4  . }
6... exd5 7. b3 Nc6 8. Bb2 Bg4
{ Now White has two options: to play against the isolani with dxc5 or go for a very symmetrical position allowing Black to take on f3 and d4. }
9. Be2 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 cxd4 11. exd4 Bb4
{ This position is very balanced: White has the bishop pair but the bishops are not that great and Black is very solid, the computer thinks that White doesn't have any advantage and it proves equality convincingly. }
12. Qe2+ Qe7 13. O-O { The simplest solution appears to be } 13... Bxc3 14.
Bxc3 Qxe2 15. Bxe2 Kd7
{ When Black is doing quite well in this endgame despite White's two bishops. }
16. Bd3 g6 17. Rfe1 Rhe8 18. f3 Nh5
{ It's quite difficult for White to create anything with the bishops, now Black's knight will reroute to e6, putting more pressure on d4. }
19. g3 Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Ng7 { Black is even a bit better in this position. } *

