{ This is by far the main continuation and as we have seen, the alternatives are not very challenging for Black.   6.Be2?!  dxc4  7.Bxc4  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3?!  dxc4  7.Bxc4  . }
6... exd5 7. Be2 { The most natural square for the bishop. } 7... Nc6 8. O-O
Bd6
{ Finally, here we have to give up the little fight for the tempo with dxc5 and the bishop development, but I think the position is very playable for Black anyway. }
9. b3 { Is possible too but not too challenging for Black with precise play. }
9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qc7
{ An important move, the double threat of ...Bxh2 and ...Nxd4 followed by ...Be5 forces White to retreat with the knight. }
11. Nf3 Be6
{ Now Black develops normally and once again gets a very good version of the IQP positions. }
12. Bb2 O-O 13. Rc1 Rad8
{ White doesn't have a lot of control over the d4-square and Black might be even threatening ...d5-d4 now. }
14. Na4 { After this logical looking move, Black gets attacking chances. }
14... Ne4 15. h3 Qe7 { We can play ...f5-f4 next or ...Bb8 preparing ...Qd6. }
