[Round "?"]
[White "6) 4.Nf3: 5th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4.Nf3: 5.e3 a6 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Be2 #10/14"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ One of the main move orders for White in this position. } 4... c5
{ Black immediately challenges White in the center, we are not yet technically speaking in Semi-Tarrasch territory. }
5. e3
{ This is the 2nd major continuation in this position apart from  5.cxd5  . It is very rich in transpositions as we could get now different openings depending on how Black plays. }
5... a6
{ After some consideration, I decided to pick this move as our main here.  The alternatives are all viable, of course, but I feel that this one gives White fewer options @@StartBracket@@which is always nice@@EndBracket@@ and at the same time, the lines are relatively easy to play and remember as Black.  We are agreeing to play with an isolated pawn now, but I believe a very decent version.  The move ...a6 is very useful in these positions as it takes control of the b5-square and also gives the a7-square for our bishop, just in case. }
6. cxd5
{ This is by far the main continuation and as we have seen, the alternatives are not very challenging for Black.   6.Be2?!  dxc4  7.Bxc4  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3?!  dxc4  7.Bxc4  . }
6... exd5 7. Be2 { The most natural square for the bishop. } 7... Nc6 8. O-O
Bd6
{ Finally, here we have to give up the little fight for the tempo with dxc5 and the bishop development, but I think the position is very playable for Black anyway. }
9. dxc5 { This makes the most sense, now that Black already moved the bishop. }
9... Bxc5 10. a3
{ Generally speaking, the a3+b4 structure is better than a2+b3 because it gives White some more space, the possibility to play b4-b5 later on and also control over the c5-square for an eventual Na4-c5.  The b3+Bb2 construction is a little more limited as we have already seen in some of the previous lines. }
10... O-O 11. b4
{ Consistent with the previous move and probably the most challenging for Black. }
11... d4
{ I want to recommend this move here. It's a very concrete solution to Black's problems in this line as we are immediately getting rid of our weakness.   The most employed move is  11...Ba7  but then White can play  12.b5  immediately with good chances to get an advantage. }
12. Na4 Ba7 13. Nc5
{ Here Black has two more or less equivalent ways to equalize. } 13... dxe3 14.
Bxe3 Re8 15. Rc1 { 15.Qxd8  Nxd8=  . } 15... Qxd1 16. Bxd1
{ 16.Rfxd1  Ng4!  and Black is obviously doing very well. } 16... h6 17. Bb3
Bxc5 18. Bxc5 Be6
{ Again, White has the two bishops but it's not enough to fight for the advantage.  If White withdraws the bishop, then Black gets ...Bd5 and the position is very close to being completely equal. }
19. Ba4 b5 20. Bc2 Bd5 21. Nd4 Nd7
{ White already loses his bishop pair and it's totally equal. } *

