{ This is the starting position of another big line in the Semi-Tarrasch. I believe this particular one, especially the move  7.Rb1  here, is the most dangerous for Black.  Black does not get to trade bishops with ...cxd4 and ...Bb4+ which means that White's space advantage and central pawn majority could play a more important role as there are more pieces on the board, but, as I am going to demonstrate, Black's position is perfectly sound and very playable at all levels. }
7. Rb1
{ Now we come to the best move for White in this position. White stops ...Bb4+ and, besides doing so, he also activates the rook. }
7... Be7
{ Now the main and most logical move for White is  8.Nf3  but there are some interesting alternatives that we will consider in this chapter. }
8. Bb5+
{ This is the 2nd most employed move here, it is quite a solid move but it is not considered to be dangerous for Black. }
8... Bd7 { Now White can choose between a few options. } 9. Nf3
{ Here we play very similarly to the way we play in the line  9.Ne2  . } 9...
Bxb5 10. Rxb5 b6 11. O-O
{ 11.d5  f5!  And White's central structure gets destroyed. Black is doing well  . }
11... O-O 12. Bf4 { 12.d5  f5!  13.exf5  Qxd5  Again is excellent for Black. }
12... Bd6
{ I like this move. White's bishop on f4 is exerting annoying pressure over our queenside  @@StartBracket@@the queen can't go to c7, d4-d5 is always hanging in the air, so that is why we want to eliminate that bishop.  After the trade @@StartBracket@@or the withdrawal@@EndBracket@@ of the bishop, we will have a lot more space and good squares for our pieces. }
13. Bxd6
{ 13.Be3  Nd7  Black will follow with ...Qc7, ...Rc8 etc. with a perfectly good position.   13.e5?!  Be7  also seems excellent for Black. The loss of a tempo matters little here as the e4-e5 push is strategically dubious for White. Black will follow with ...Nc6, ...Rc8 and so on with very good counterplay. }
13... Qxd6 14. dxc5 Qc7
{ We sac a pawn, but in this type of position Black gets very good compensation because most of White's pawns are very vulnerable. }
15. cxb6 axb6 { Black is doing well. } *

