1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5
{ This is one of the main lines and White's idea is to meet  4...exd5  with  5.Bg5  with the famous Carlsbad structure which slightly favors White.   The options gained by White with this move order are mainly connected to the position reached after  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  and here White has a few options other than  7.Nf3  .  Most notably the line with  7.Rb1  which I argue is one of the most dangerous systems in the whole course.   White can also transpose back to 4.Nf3 lines in a couple of instances, for example, after  4...Nxd5  White could play  5.Nf3  here when Black would play  5...c5  . }
4... Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5
{ This is the starting position of another big line in the Semi-Tarrasch. I believe this particular one, especially the move  7.Rb1  here, is the most dangerous for Black.  Black does not get to trade bishops with ...cxd4 and ...Bb4+ which means that White's space advantage and central pawn majority could play a more important role as there are more pieces on the board, but, as I am going to demonstrate, Black's position is perfectly sound and very playable at all levels. }
7. Rb1
{ Now we come to the best move for White in this position. White stops ...Bb4+ and, besides doing so, he also activates the rook. }
7... Be7
{ Now the main and most logical move for White is  8.Nf3  but there are some interesting alternatives that we will consider in this chapter. }
8. h4
{ An interesting and tricky idea. White throws his pawn first, trying to create weaknesses in Black's camp and at the same time keeps open the option of Qg4. }
8... O-O 9. h5
{ 9.Nf3  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/4p3/2p5/3PP3/2P5/P4PPP/1RBQKBNR w Kkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nf3  O-O  9.h4  lines. }
9... h6
{ I don't like to allow h5-h6 as it will create a long term problem for us regarding the safety of our king. }
10. Qg4
{ The most logical follow up and the one Carlsen played against me in a rapid game, although as we will see, it is actually very concrete and gives White no more than a draw.   10.Nf3  b6  would transpose to the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/4p3/2p5/3PP3/2P5/P4PPP/1RBQKBNR w Kkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nf3  O-O  9.h4  b6  10.h5  h6  . }
10... Kh8 11. e5 cxd4 { Play now gets a very forcing character } 12. Bd3
{ The best way to set up the battery threat with Qe4.   12.Qe4?  Qd5∓  And White is not in time for Bd3.   12.cxd4?  Nc6  13.Nf3  Bb4+!  transposes to the variation  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1r1k/pp2bpp1/4p2p/2p4P/3PP1Q1/2P5/P4PP1/1RB1KBNR w K - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Nf3  cxd4  12.cxd4  Nc6  13.e5  Bb4+  . }
12... Nd7
{ The only response, but quite enough. Now White has two tries but none of them promises anything. Let's see }
13. Bxh6 { The most dangerous. } 13... gxh6
{ As I mentioned earlier, play is super forcing now. } 14. Qe4 f5 15. exf6 Nxf6
16. Qg6 Qc7
{ The only move we have to make sure we remember but it is very logical.  White's main ideas are connected to a rook transfer via h3-g3 and b5-g5. We can cover the g3-square with ...Bd6 and block the 5th rank with ...e5 or sometimes ...Nd5.  White has nothing more than a draw here. }
17. Qxh6+ Kg8 18. Rh3 Bd6 19. Rb5 Nd5
{ Is losing for White, we see here the main point of ...Qc7, protecting the h7-square. }
*

