{ This has been tried a few times but the knight on e2 stands worse than on f3 @@StartBracket@@unlike the Grunfeld, here White does not need to worry about Bg4@@EndBracket@@ so Black gets a nice game by simple means.   9.Nf3  Transposes to our main line with 8.Nf3 O-O 9.Bc4. }
9... Nc6 10. O-O b6
{ This seems the most harmonious way of developing our forces here. We are planning ...Bb7, ...Rc8 and then something like ...cxd4, ...Na5 and ...Nc4 with clear counterplay on the queenside.  Again, this type of play resembles the Grunfeld and having e6 and Be7 here instead of g6, Bg7 in a way feels even more sound for Black. }
11. Be3 Bb7 12. Nf4
{ This would be the most logical way to make sense of Ne2 but in fact, Black can keep playing the normal moves without having to worry about Nxe6. }
12... Rc8
{ 12...cxd4?!  13.cxd4  Na5  14.Bd3  Rc8  Is not good here, because then  15.Qg4!  ↑ is very strong with a huge initiative and one important point is that after  15...Nc4?  16.Nxe6!  +-  wins for White. }
13. Nxe6
{ This leads to an unbalanced position but one that is quite acceptable for Black, I think. }
13... fxe6 14. Bxe6+ Kh8 15. Bxc8 Qxc8
{ With a complicated position in which Black's chances are not worse, in fact, I would prefer to be Black here as I see more potential for the minor pieces than for White's rooks. For instance }
16. Qa4 Na5 17. dxc5 Bc6 18. Qd1 Bxe4
{ Was played in Grachev-Melkumyan, World Cup 2017 with a big advantage for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 4.cxd5: 5.e4 − 7.Rb1 Be7 Without 8.Nf3"]
[Black "4.cxd5: 5.e4 − 7.Rb1 Be7 8.Bc4 #5/5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5
{ This is one of the main lines and White's idea is to meet  4...exd5  with  5.Bg5  with the famous Carlsbad structure which slightly favors White.   The options gained by White with this move order are mainly connected to the position reached after  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  and here White has a few options other than  7.Nf3  .  Most notably the line with  7.Rb1  which I argue is one of the most dangerous systems in the whole course.   White can also transpose back to 4.Nf3 lines in a couple of instances, for example, after  4...Nxd5  White could play  5.Nf3  here when Black would play  5...c5  . }
4... Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5
{ This is the starting position of another big line in the Semi-Tarrasch. I believe this particular one, especially the move  7.Rb1  here, is the most dangerous for Black.  Black does not get to trade bishops with ...cxd4 and ...Bb4+ which means that White's space advantage and central pawn majority could play a more important role as there are more pieces on the board, but, as I am going to demonstrate, Black's position is perfectly sound and very playable at all levels. }
7. Rb1
{ Now we come to the best move for White in this position. White stops ...Bb4+ and, besides doing so, he also activates the rook. }
7... Be7
{ Now the main and most logical move for White is  8.Nf3  but there are some interesting alternatives that we will consider in this chapter. }
8. Bc4 O-O 9. Ne2
{ This has been tried a few times but the knight on e2 stands worse than on f3 @@StartBracket@@unlike the Grunfeld, here White does not need to worry about Bg4@@EndBracket@@ so Black gets a nice game by simple means.   9.Nf3  Transposes to our main line with 8.Nf3 O-O 9.Bc4. }
9... Nc6 10. O-O b6
{ This seems the most harmonious way of developing our forces here. We are planning ...Bb7, ...Rc8 and then something like ...cxd4, ...Na5 and ...Nc4 with clear counterplay on the queenside.  Again, this type of play resembles the Grunfeld and having e6 and Be7 here instead of g6, Bg7 in a way feels even more sound for Black. }
11. Be3 Bb7 12. Nf4
{ This would be the most logical way to make sense of Ne2 but in fact, Black can keep playing the normal moves without having to worry about Nxe6. }
12... Rc8
{ 12...cxd4?!  13.cxd4  Na5  14.Bd3  Rc8  Is not good here, because then  15.Qg4!  ↑ is very strong with a huge initiative and one important point is that after  15...Nc4?  16.Nxe6!  +-  wins for White. }
13. Nxe6
{ This leads to an unbalanced position but one that is quite acceptable for Black, I think. }
13... fxe6 14. Bxe6+ Kh8 15. Bxc8 Qxc8
{ With a complicated position in which Black's chances are not worse, in fact, I would prefer to be Black here as I see more potential for the minor pieces than for White's rooks. For instance }
16. Re1 Na5 17. f3 Nc4 18. Bf2 h6
{ And after what seems to be the best play from both sides, the evaluation hasn't changed, Black's chances are by no means worse in this complex position. }
*

