{ I prefer Black's chances in this position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 4.cxd5: 5.e4 − 7.Rb1 − Other 9th Moves"]
[Black "4.cxd5: 5.e4 − 7.Rb1 − 9.Be2 #2/6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5
{ This is one of the main lines and White's idea is to meet  4...exd5  with  5.Bg5  with the famous Carlsbad structure which slightly favors White.   The options gained by White with this move order are mainly connected to the position reached after  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  and here White has a few options other than  7.Nf3  .  Most notably the line with  7.Rb1  which I argue is one of the most dangerous systems in the whole course.   White can also transpose back to 4.Nf3 lines in a couple of instances, for example, after  4...Nxd5  White could play  5.Nf3  here when Black would play  5...c5  . }
4... Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5
{ This is the starting position of another big line in the Semi-Tarrasch. I believe this particular one, especially the move  7.Rb1  here, is the most dangerous for Black.  Black does not get to trade bishops with ...cxd4 and ...Bb4+ which means that White's space advantage and central pawn majority could play a more important role as there are more pieces on the board, but, as I am going to demonstrate, Black's position is perfectly sound and very playable at all levels. }
7. Rb1
{ Now we come to the best move for White in this position. White stops ...Bb4+ and, besides doing so, he also activates the rook. }
7... Be7 8. Nf3 O-O
{ Now the two main continuations for White are  9.Bc4  and  9.h4  . We will consider each one of them carefully in the next chapters but first, let's take a look at some other moves White could play here. }
9. Be2
{ A solid move, but not without venom. White simply wants to finish development and then try to use his central pawn majority and space advantage. }
9... b6
{ Now that the e4-pawn is unprotected, this way of developing makes a lot of sense as we will win a tempo with ...Bb7. }
10. O-O Bb7 11. Qd3
{ This has been played by Carlsen and Ding Liren and indeed seems the best way to defend the pawn, also preparing Rd1.   11.Bd3?!  is not great as after  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  Nc6  13.Be3  Black has the strong  13...Nb4∓  Followed by taking the bishop with clearly the better game. }
11... Ba6
{ There are several ways that Black can go here but I like this one as Black's play is quite straightforward.  Also, let's not forget that in general, we should welcome exchanges in this opening and the light-squared bishops are no exception to this rule. }
12. Qe3 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 cxd4 14. cxd4 Nd7
{ After a few forced moves, we get this position, which seems to me to be quite easy to play for Black.  Our main idea is to get counterplay on the c-file with ...Rc8 and if possible ...Qc7 and ...Qc2 or ...Qc4, but also b7 and a4 are good squares for our queen. The knight will usually go to f6. }
15. Rd1 { Was played in Ding Liren-Dominguez, St Louis blitz 2019. } 15... Qc7
{ This is the simplest move, stopping Bf4 and preparing ...Rac8. Black is quite comfortable already. }
*

