11... Bb7
{ It's important to give the lines after this move but only for informational purposes. Just to be able to appreciate the advantages of  11...Nd7  .   11...cxd4  12.cxd4  e5?  It's also bad for Black as after  13.Rg3+-  White wins. }
12. Bd3 Nd7
{ 12...cxd4?!  13.cxd4  Nc6   13...e5  Now it is already too late for this and after  14.Rg3  Kh8  15.Nxe5  Qxd4  16.Bb2  Qb4+  17.Kf1+-  White gets a devastating attack  14.Rg3  Kh8  15.Qd2!  A typical motif that we will also see later in our main line but here is very strong  15...Rg8  16.Kf1  White gets his king to safety first and then strikes in the center with d4-d5  16...Rc8   16...Nxd4  17.Nxd4  Qxd4  18.Bb2+-  White wins on the spot  17.d5!  exd5  18.exd5  Qxd5  19.Bb2  19...f6  20.Nh4+-  And Black is defenseless against Ng6. }
13. Rg3 Kh8 14. Qd2 { Again this is strong, forcing the black rook to g8. }
14... Rg8 { 14...cxd4?  15.Rxg7+-  loses immediately. } 15. Kf1 Rc8 16. Kg1
cxd4 17. cxd4 Nf6 18. Qe1
{ Black's position is quite unpleasant here, White will slowly increase the pressure and it's not so easy for Black to create counterplay.   18.Qe2?  Nxh5  19.Rh3  Rxc1+!  This shows the point of the 18.Qe1.  20.Rxc1  Nf4-+  . }
18... Nxh5 { Now doesn't work. } 19. Rh3 Rxc1 20. Qxc1
{ And the queen protects the f4-square. White is winning. } *

