4... Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5
{ This is the starting position of another big line in the Semi-Tarrasch. I believe this particular one, especially the move  7.Rb1  here, is the most dangerous for Black.  Black does not get to trade bishops with ...cxd4 and ...Bb4+ which means that White's space advantage and central pawn majority could play a more important role as there are more pieces on the board, but, as I am going to demonstrate, Black's position is perfectly sound and very playable at all levels. }
7. Rb1
{ Now we come to the best move for White in this position. White stops ...Bb4+ and, besides doing so, he also activates the rook. }
7... Be7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. h4
{ Statistically speaking, this move is the 2nd most employed @@StartBracket@@ after  9.Bc4  @@EndBracket@@, but in practical terms, I think it is probably the most dangerous for Black.   As usual with this pawn advance, it seeks to create weaknesses in Black's kingside. Also, White will have the Rh3-g3 resource in many lines. }
9... b6
{ After careful analysis I decided to recommend this move here.   Alternatives such as  9...cxd4  and  9...Nc6  are playable too but I like the fact that the lines after  9...b6  are a bit less explored.    In general, once you go deep in this line, it can get very complicated and super forcing, in some lines White will throw everything on the kingside and we will take material and repel the attack with very precise and often only moves.  Needless to say, this particular branch requires good memorization.  Now, all of that said, I firmly believe the line is 100% sound for Black and I hope that equipped with the knowledge I will try to provide here, you will be able to feel confident and successfully implement it in practice. }
10. h5
{ The most logical move and the only one that has been tried in practice. }
10... h6
{ Again, we do not want to allow h5-h6 to create long term problems for our king. }
11. Rh3
{ Even though it is almost a novelty, this move is very natural and the most challenging continuation for Black, so I decided to promote it as our main line. }
11... Nd7
{ A very important move, we have to remember to start with this move here and not  11...Bb7  @@StartBracket@@see informational@@EndBracket@@ which also seems natural.  The main point, as we will see in the variations, is that by starting with  11...Nd7  Black has the very important ...e6-e5 resource @@StartBracket@@after trading pawns on d4@@EndBracket@@ almost all the time and that is not the case with  11...Bb7  . }
12. Rg3 { This seems to me to be the most tricky for Black. } 12... Kh8 13. Qd2
{ White immediately prepares the Rxg7 shot, without Bd3.   Now in case of  13...Rg8  he will have some additional options.   13.Bd3  cxd4  14.cxd4  e5!  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p2nbpp1/1p2p2p/2p4P/3PP3/2P2N1R/P4PP1/1RBQKB2 w - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bd3  cxd4  13.cxd4  e5  14.Rg3  Kh8  . }
13... cxd4 { The immediate } 14. Rxg7 { is also possible but after } 14... Kxg7
15. Qxh6+ Kg8 { White has not more than a draw, for example, after } 16. e5 Nc5
{ Stopping Bd3. } 17. Ng5 Bxg5 18. Bxg5 Qd5 19. Bf6 Qe4+
{ And now it is Black who gives perpetual check in the following forced line: }
20. Kd2 dxc3+ 21. Kxc3 Na4+ 22. Kd2 Rd8+
{ Deflecting the bishop.   22...Qd4+?  This move doesn't quite work the same way without the ...Rd8 intermezzo, but it's useful to see why so that we can appreciate the difference.  23.Bd3  Qxf2+  24.Kc1!  Qe1+  25.Kc2  Qc3+  It looks that White loses everything with check but in fact after  26.Kd1  Qxd3+  27.Ke1  Qxb1+  28.Kf2  Qc2+  29.Kg3  Qd3+  30.Kh2+-  The white king escapes and Black gets mated.   @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p4p2/1p2pB1Q/4P2P/n7/3B4/P1K3P1/1R2q3 b - - 3 25@@EndFEN@@  25...Qf2+  26.Kb3  Nc5+  27.Ka3+-  Also wins for White. }
23. Bxd8 Qd4+ 24. Bd3 Qxf2+ 25. Kd1
{ 25.Kc1?  White's bishop is no longer on f6 threatening mate, so this doesn't work for White now.  25...Qe1+  26.Kc2  Qc3+  27.Kd1  Qxd3+  28.Ke1  Qxb1+  29.Kf2  Nc3-+  Black wins. }
25... Nc3+ 26. Kc1 Nxa2+ { With a draw by repetition. } 27. Kd1 Nc3+ *

