[White "11) 4.cxd5: 5.e4 − 7.Rb1 − 9.Bc4 Main Line"]
[Black "4.cxd5: 5.e4 − 7.Rb1 − 9.Bc4 Qc7 10.Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5
{ This is one of the main lines and White's idea is to meet  4...exd5  with  5.Bg5  with the famous Carlsbad structure which slightly favors White.   The options gained by White with this move order are mainly connected to the position reached after  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  and here White has a few options other than  7.Nf3  .  Most notably the line with  7.Rb1  which I argue is one of the most dangerous systems in the whole course.   White can also transpose back to 4.Nf3 lines in a couple of instances, for example, after  4...Nxd5  White could play  5.Nf3  here when Black would play  5...c5  . }
4... Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5
{ This is the starting position of another big line in the Semi-Tarrasch. I believe this particular one, especially the move  7.Rb1  here, is the most dangerous for Black.  Black does not get to trade bishops with ...cxd4 and ...Bb4+ which means that White's space advantage and central pawn majority could play a more important role as there are more pieces on the board, but, as I am going to demonstrate, Black's position is perfectly sound and very playable at all levels. }
7. Rb1
{ Now we come to the best move for White in this position. White stops ...Bb4+ and, besides doing so, he also activates the rook. }
7... Be7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bc4
{ Finally we come to the main line. White places his bishop on the most active square while preparing to castle. Now the d4-d5 push gains in strength so we must be careful. }
9... Qc7
{ Alternatives to  10.Qe2  are not very promising for White, for example: } 10.
Bd3 Nc6
{ In general, the drawback of Bd3 is that it leaves the d4-pawn somewhat undefended, so usually the best response for Black is to put pressure on the pawn immediately. }
11. O-O cxd4 12. cxd4 Nb4
{ An important point, White is not in time to save the light-squared bishop. }
13. Ba3
{ 13.Be2?  Nxa2  14.Bd2  Nc3  15.Bxc3  Qxc3∓  Black is clearly better as there is no compensation for the pawn. }
13... Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Bxa3 15. Qxa3 b6
{ If Black gets time to develop the bishop then the situation will be quite promising, positionally speaking, because the bishop seems a little stronger than the knight and the endgame prospects are great for Black with the 2 vs 1 on the queenside.  White has to try to act fast but there seems to be nothing special, for example }
16. Rbc1
{ 16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Rd8⇆  Also looks excellent for Black, the pawn seems rather weak and White has no real way to build an initiative. }
16... Qf4
{ A nice square, now White has to worry about the e4-pawn. Also, it's important to leave the d8-square available for the black rooks while White has the chance to play d4-d5.   16...Qd8?  This might seem logical too, especially after reviewing our main line with 16...Qf4, but the problem is that now White can push the d-pawn all the way and our queen would be very badly placed.  17.Rfd1  Bb7  18.d5!  exd5  19.exd5±  with d6 to follow and in case of  19...Bxd5  20.Rd4+-  just wins for White. }
17. Rfe1 Bb7 18. g3 Qb8
{ It's important to prevent White's rook invasion on c7. } 19. Ne5 Qd8
{ Avoiding Nd7 and Qe7 ideas. Our queen returned to d8 but now White doesn't have d5 anymore and Black has nothing to fear. ...Rc8 might follow or in some instances ...f7-f5 as well, exploiting the weaknesses along the h1-a8 diagonal. }
20. Rcd1 f5 { Would be an example, Black has a good position. } *

