20... Rfe8 21. Qd3 a5
{ The position is roughly balanced. Again, White has the better pawn structure but this is compensated by the fact that all of Black's pieces are active and well placed. He can even sac the a-pawn in some lines and still get enough play. }
22. Bd2 Rb2 23. Qc3 Qb8 24. Re1 Rxe1+ 25. Nxe1 Bg6 26. Bxg6 hxg6
{ With strong counterplay for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 4.cxd5: 5.e4 − 7.Rb1 − 9.Bc4 Main Line"]
[Black "4.cxd5: 5.e4 − 7.Rb1 − 9.Bc4 Qc7 10.Qe2 a6 11.Bd3 b5 12.O-O #21/25"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5
{ This is one of the main lines and White's idea is to meet  4...exd5  with  5.Bg5  with the famous Carlsbad structure which slightly favors White.   The options gained by White with this move order are mainly connected to the position reached after  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  and here White has a few options other than  7.Nf3  .  Most notably the line with  7.Rb1  which I argue is one of the most dangerous systems in the whole course.   White can also transpose back to 4.Nf3 lines in a couple of instances, for example, after  4...Nxd5  White could play  5.Nf3  here when Black would play  5...c5  . }
4... Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5
{ This is the starting position of another big line in the Semi-Tarrasch. I believe this particular one, especially the move  7.Rb1  here, is the most dangerous for Black.  Black does not get to trade bishops with ...cxd4 and ...Bb4+ which means that White's space advantage and central pawn majority could play a more important role as there are more pieces on the board, but, as I am going to demonstrate, Black's position is perfectly sound and very playable at all levels. }
7. Rb1
{ Now we come to the best move for White in this position. White stops ...Bb4+ and, besides doing so, he also activates the rook. }
7... Be7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bc4
{ Finally we come to the main line. White places his bishop on the most active square while preparing to castle. Now the d4-d5 push gains in strength so we must be careful. }
9... Qc7
{ I want to suggest this system here. In fact, I introduced it in practice in my game against Navara in 2017.  I have analyzed it a great deal obviously and still think it is very sound and interesting for Black. }
10. Qe2 { This is the best by far. } 10... a6
{ With the obvious intention of going ...b7-b5, White can try to prevent it with the logical a2-a4 but there is a drawback to it... }
11. Bd3
{ 11.h4  b5  12.Bd3  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/1pq1bppp/p3p3/2p5/2BPP3/2P2N2/P3QPPP/1RB1K2R w K - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bd3  b5  12.h4  . }
11... b5
{ In general, playing with ...a6 and ...b5 instead of ...b6 seems quite desirable for Black.  Now Black has more space, which means more squares for our pieces on the queenside @@StartBracket@@b6 for the knight, for instance@@EndBracket@@.  The only drawback seems to be that White could have the a2-a4 resource at some point to attack Black's structure, so we have to be careful about that. }
12. O-O { This is clearly the most logical move. } 12... Nd7
{ Another very important moment to remember.   12...Bb7?!  looks very logical too but in fact, it is a very serious mistake as after  13.a4!  bxa4  14.Bf4!  ±  Carlsen-So, Internet Blitz 2017, Black stands clearly worse already.    Now White has a big choice. }
13. a4 bxa4 14. d5
{ Using the fact that Black doesn't have ...c5-c4 anymore to build an advantage in the center with an eventual c3-c4.   The alternatives are easier for Black to deal with.  14.Ra1  Would be a bit too slow  14...Bb7  15.Rxa4  a5⇆  Black is fully developed and has excellent counterplay on the queenside. }
14... exd5 15. exd5 Nf6 16. c4 Bg4
{ Although there are only a few games played, this position can probably be considered the main line in the whole 9.Bc4 Qc7 system.  White has managed to consolidate the center with c3-c4 but Black was able to complete his development and all the pieces will find good squares, moves like ...Bd6, ...Rfe8, ...Ne4 and ...Rab8 are all very natural and we will see them in some form or another in almost every single line from here on.  The defect in the pawn structure is very well compensated by Black's active pieces.  After playing the position a couple of times and of course, after a great deal of analysis, I believe that Black's chances are not worse.  Let's take a look at the main options. }
17. h3
{ First of all, there is no way for White to avoid this move as Black will play ...Bd6 anyway. }
17... Bh5 18. Ra1 { The most natural, going after the pawn straight away. }
18... Bd6
{ As we said before, Black doesn't really care so much about the a-pawns but instead focuses on getting all the pieces quickly to the most active squares.  Also, we are still up a pawn so White is only evening the material after taking on a4. In some situations as we will see, we even give both a-pawns and get a nice initiative in return. }
19. Bc2 { Still, Black continues normally with } 19... Rab8
{ Getting the rook to the open file and waiting to see how White will take on a4. }
20. Rxa4
{ If  20.Bxa4  then  20...Rb4!  ⇆  is excellent for Black with ...Bxf3 to follow and the c4-pawn will most likely fall. }
20... Rfe8 21. Qd3 a5
{ The position is roughly balanced. Again, White has the better pawn structure but this is compensated by the fact that all of Black's pieces are active and well placed. He can even sac the a-pawn in some lines and still get enough play. }
22. Bd2 Rb2 23. Bxa5 Qb8 24. Bd1 Ne4 { Is very good for Black. } *

