[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5
{ This is one of the main lines and White's idea is to meet  4...exd5  with  5.Bg5  with the famous Carlsbad structure which slightly favors White.   The options gained by White with this move order are mainly connected to the position reached after  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  and here White has a few options other than  7.Nf3  .  Most notably the line with  7.Rb1  which I argue is one of the most dangerous systems in the whole course.   White can also transpose back to 4.Nf3 lines in a couple of instances, for example, after  4...Nxd5  White could play  5.Nf3  here when Black would play  5...c5  . }
4... Nxd5
{ Here  5.e4  is by far the main move, but White has a couple of minor alternatives which we will cover in this chapter. }
5. g3
{ This is similar to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.g3  @@StartBracket@@chapter 5@@EndBracket@@.   5.e4  is the main line and will be covered in chapters7,8,9,10 and11.   5.Nf3  c5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  @@StartBracket@@chapters1,2,3,4@@EndBracket@@ and 5. }
5... c5 6. Bg2 { 6.Nf3  would transpose to the aforementioned line  . } 6...
Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. Qxd4
{ Has been tried a few times as well but it is hard to believe in it. } 8...
Nc6 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Nf3 f6
{ Once again this move is important with the same ideas. We stop Ng5 ideas and prepare for ...e6-e5. }
11. Nd4 Bd7 12. Rb1 e5 13. Nxc6+ bxc6
{ Our king will be very safe on c7 and also more active than White's monarch in the ensuing endgame. Only Black can be better here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 4.cxd5: 5.g3 & 5.e3"]
[Black "4.cxd5: 5.g3 #3/3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5
{ This is one of the main lines and White's idea is to meet  4...exd5  with  5.Bg5  with the famous Carlsbad structure which slightly favors White.   The options gained by White with this move order are mainly connected to the position reached after  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  and here White has a few options other than  7.Nf3  .  Most notably the line with  7.Rb1  which I argue is one of the most dangerous systems in the whole course.   White can also transpose back to 4.Nf3 lines in a couple of instances, for example, after  4...Nxd5  White could play  5.Nf3  here when Black would play  5...c5  . }
4... Nxd5
{ Here  5.e4  is by far the main move, but White has a couple of minor alternatives which we will cover in this chapter. }
5. g3
{ This is similar to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.g3  @@StartBracket@@chapter 5@@EndBracket@@.   5.e4  is the main line and will be covered in chapters7,8,9,10 and11.   5.Nf3  c5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  @@StartBracket@@chapters1,2,3,4@@EndBracket@@ and 5. }
5... c5 6. Bg2 { 6.Nf3  would transpose to the aforementioned line  . } 6...
Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4
{ The most ambitious move, but it does not offer much to White. } 8... Bb4+
{ This is of course the problem with the pawn recapture in the center. Now White is pretty much forced to move the king @@StartBracket@@d4 is hanging after Bd2@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Kf1 Nc6 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Nf3 Bd7
{ Black calmly finishes development and prepares the usual counterplay on the queenside, particularly on the c-file.  If White would have the normal castle position, with the king on g1 and rook on f1, the position would be clearly better because the white bishops are well placed on the long diagonals and the center is superior.  With the king on f1 though, the evaluation changes dramatically because it's very hard to bring the king's rook into play.  I would say it's more or less balanced now but it's probably easier to play for Black. }
12. h4 Rc8 13. Qd3 f6
{ A good move, not only stopping Ng5 but also preparing ...Na5-c4 as now the e5-square is protected as well. }
14. Kg1 Na5 15. Kh2
{ We see how long it took White to finally connect the rooks, in the meantime, Black already built his queenside counterplay. }
15... Nc4 16. Rab1 Qe7 17. Bc1 b5 18. Rd1 a5
{ Black had some advantage in the game Korobov-Berkes, Moscow 2017. A natural plan would be to play ...Rfd8 and ...Be8-g6 next. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 4.cxd5: 5.g3 & 5.e3"]
[Black "4.cxd5: 5.e3 #1/9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5
{ This is one of the main lines and White's idea is to meet  4...exd5  with  5.Bg5  with the famous Carlsbad structure which slightly favors White.   The options gained by White with this move order are mainly connected to the position reached after  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  and here White has a few options other than  7.Nf3  .  Most notably the line with  7.Rb1  which I argue is one of the most dangerous systems in the whole course.   White can also transpose back to 4.Nf3 lines in a couple of instances, for example, after  4...Nxd5  White could play  5.Nf3  here when Black would play  5...c5  . }
4... Nxd5
{ Here  5.e4  is by far the main move, but White has a couple of minor alternatives which we will cover in this chapter. }
5. e3
{ A solid move, similar to the line with Nf3 and ...c7-c5 included, but there are some differences as we will see.   5.e4  is the main line and will be covered in chapters7,8,9,10 and11.   5.Nf3  c5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  @@StartBracket@@chapters1,2,3 and4@@EndBracket@@. }
5... c5 6. Bd3
{ White keeps developing but without playing Nf3. This move order was used in the game Carlsen-Hou Yifan, Tata Steel 2018.   6.Nf3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e3  @@StartBracket@@chapter 3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... cxd4 7. exd4 g6
{ I like this solution here.   7...Nxc3  If Black plays like this then we see what is the point behind White's move order.  8.bxc3  Qc7  9.Bd2  Nd7  10.Qg4!?  Now White has this resource @@StartBracket@@thanks to the fact that Nf3 has not been played@@EndBracket@@ and even though it is not killing, it does offer White a slightly better endgame after  10...Nf6  11.Qg3  Qxg3  12.hxg3⩲  . This is how Carlsen beat Hou Yifan in the aforementioned game. }
8. h4 { A very principled way to deal with the ...g6, ...Bg7 idea. } 8... Bg7
9. h5 Nc6 10. Nf3 O-O
{ It might seem a little risky to castle just right after White went h4-h5 but it's not so clear how White can successfully create problems for us in the kingside whereas we are getting ready to counterattack in the center.  For example, now ...Nxd4 is a threat @@StartBracket@@it wasn't possible earlier due to Qa4+@@EndBracket@@ and also moves like ...e6-e5 opening up the position, are very much on the table. }
11. Be4 { White defends the central pawn. } 11... Qb6 { Renewing the threat. }
12. Na4 Qb4+ 13. Bd2 Qb5 14. hxg6 hxg6 { Black is doing well here. } 15. Qc2
{ Was played in Ding-Wei Yi, Danzhou 2020 and now } 15... Bd7
{ would have been strong. } 16. Nc3 Ncb4 17. Qb1 Qc4 18. a3 Nxc3 19. Bxc3 Nd5
{ With ...Bb5, ...Rac8 and ...Rfd8 to follow and Black is just much better. } *

