8. Nf3 Bg7 9. O-O
{ 9.h4  Nc6  10.h5  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3p1p/4p1p1/3n4/3P4/2NB4/PP3PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h4  Bg7  9.h5  Nc6  10.Nf3  . }
9... O-O 10. Bg5 Qb6 11. Bc4 { 11.Qd2  Nc6  is just ok for Black. } 11... Nxc3
12. bxc3 Qc7
{ Here we switch to playing against the hanging pawns. Black has a very decent version now with ...b6 and ...Bb7 to follow. }
13. Bb3 b6 14. Re1 Bb7 15. Qd3 Nd7
{ The position is close to equal objectively but I like Black's chances in practice, due to the potential weakness of the c3- and d4-pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 4.cxd5: 5.g3 & 5.e3"]
[Black "4.cxd5: 5.e3 #6/9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5
{ This is one of the main lines and White's idea is to meet  4...exd5  with  5.Bg5  with the famous Carlsbad structure which slightly favors White.   The options gained by White with this move order are mainly connected to the position reached after  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  c5  and here White has a few options other than  7.Nf3  .  Most notably the line with  7.Rb1  which I argue is one of the most dangerous systems in the whole course.   White can also transpose back to 4.Nf3 lines in a couple of instances, for example, after  4...Nxd5  White could play  5.Nf3  here when Black would play  5...c5  . }
4... Nxd5
{ Here  5.e4  is by far the main move, but White has a couple of minor alternatives which we will cover in this chapter. }
5. e3
{ A solid move, similar to the line with Nf3 and ...c7-c5 included, but there are some differences as we will see.   5.e4  is the main line and will be covered in chapters7,8,9,10 and11.   5.Nf3  c5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  @@StartBracket@@chapters1,2,3 and4@@EndBracket@@. }
5... c5 6. Bd3
{ White keeps developing but without playing Nf3. This move order was used in the game Carlsen-Hou Yifan, Tata Steel 2018.   6.Nf3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e3  @@StartBracket@@chapter 3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... cxd4 7. exd4 g6
{ I like this solution here.   7...Nxc3  If Black plays like this then we see what is the point behind White's move order.  8.bxc3  Qc7  9.Bd2  Nd7  10.Qg4!?  Now White has this resource @@StartBracket@@thanks to the fact that Nf3 has not been played@@EndBracket@@ and even though it is not killing, it does offer White a slightly better endgame after  10...Nf6  11.Qg3  Qxg3  12.hxg3⩲  . This is how Carlsen beat Hou Yifan in the aforementioned game. }
8. Nf3 Bg7 9. O-O
{ 9.h4  Nc6  10.h5  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3p1p/4p1p1/3n4/3P4/2NB4/PP3PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h4  Bg7  9.h5  Nc6  10.Nf3  . }
9... O-O 10. Bg5 Qb6 11. Na4
{ This was played in the only practical example that we have from this position. I checked some other possibilities here as well.   11.Qd2  Nc6  is just ok for Black. }
11... Qd6 12. Rc1 Nc6 13. Be4
{ This was played in the game Sargissian-Keymer, EU ch Online 2020. } 13... h6
{ And now it was precise to kick the bishop out of the h4-d8 diagonal so that our rook gets the d8-square. }
14. Bd2 { 14.Bh4?  f5!  ∓  is just bad for White. } 14... Rd8
{ Black has consolidated his position and is already slightly better. } *

