1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ In this chapter, we will take a look at the alternatives to  4.cxd5  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bf4
{ This move is much less common and Black indeed solves his problems relatively easy after }
4... c5 { The immediate strike in the center works well for us here. } 5. e3
{ 5.Nf3  would transpose to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c5  5.Bf4  . }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Be7 7. c5
{ After  7.c5  Black gets counterplay with the typical undermining move ...b7-b6. }
7... O-O 8. Nf3 b6 9. b4 Ne4
{ Immediately taking advantage of the fact that the c3-knight lost support. }
10. Qc2 Nc6 { Black already has the initiative. } 11. a3 bxc5 12. bxc5
{ This normal move even loses directly! } 12... Qa5 13. Rc1 e5
{ For example,  14.Bxe5  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Bg5-+  wins material. } *

