[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Other 4th moves: 4.Bg5 (And 4.Bf4)"]
[Black "Other 4th moves: 4.Bg5 Be7 5.e3 #1/7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ In this chapter, we will take a look at the alternatives to  4.cxd5  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bg5
{ This move is actually the most employed in this position, but it is also true that modern theory considers  4.Nf3  and especially  4.cxd5  to be more challenging for Black.  So we can not really call  4.Bg5  a sideline as it is a very principal option here but it has lost popularity over the aforementioned alternatives in practice in the last few years. }
4... Be7
{ We enter the classical Queen's Gambit Declined territory but these lines with Bg5 instead of Bf4 are actually not especially dangerous for Black. }
5. e3 h6 6. Bh4
{ 6.Bxf6  Bxf6  7.Nf3  would transpose to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p2B1/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  h6  6.Bxf6  Bxf6  7.e3  . }
6... dxc4
{ There are many viable ways to play for Black here, but I want to suggest this line which is very much similar to what we do in the 5.Nf3 lines. It is quite rare in this specific position though. }
7. Bxc4 c5 8. dxc5
{ 8.Nf3  would transpose to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p2B1/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  h6  6.Bh4  dxc4  7.e3  c5  8.Bxc4  . }
8... Qxd1+ 9. Rxd1 Nbd7 { Black simply wants to recapture the pawn. } 10. Nb5
{ 10.c6  bxc6  and White has nothing better than  11.Nf3  transposing again to the main line.   11.Nge2?  would be careless in view of  11...Ne5!  12.Bb3  Ba6  when White is actually in trouble   11.Bg3  Nb6⇆  is also fine for Black.   10.Nf3  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p2B1/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  h6  6.Bh4  dxc4  7.e3  c5  8.dxc5  Qxd1+  9.Rxd1  Nbd7  10.Bxc4  . }
10... O-O 11. Nc7 Rb8 12. Nxe6 { 12.b4  b6⇆  . } 12... fxe6 13. Bxe6+ Rf7
{ The resulting position with a rook for 2 minor pieces is complex but I feel that Black's chances are not worse, the computer more or less agrees.   Note that  13...Kh7?  fails to  14.Bxd7  Bxd7  15.Bxf6+-  . }
14. Bg3 Ra8 15. b4 a5 16. a3 b6
{ Black doesn't hurry with the pawn trades as the a3-pawn can be attacked, for example,  17.Bd6  Bxd6  18.cxd6  Ne5  19.Bxf7+  Kxf7  20.Nf3  Nc4⇆  Black is doing well. }
