10... bxc6 11. Bxc4
{ Now White can still hope because at least structurally there is an advantage due to the weak a- and c-pawns.  In reality though, Black has enough time to create a lot of play, mainly using the ...Rb8+...Nd5 combination, the b2-pawn is not easy to defend for White. }
11... Rb8 12. Rd2 Nd5 13. Bxe7 Kxe7 14. Na4 N5b6 15. Nxb6 axb6
{ Black convincingly equalized in the game Aravindh-Adams, London blitz 2019. }
*

