1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ In this chapter, we will take a look at the alternatives to  4.cxd5  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bg5
{ This move is actually the most employed in this position, but it is also true that modern theory considers  4.Nf3  and especially  4.cxd5  to be more challenging for Black.  So we can not really call  4.Bg5  a sideline as it is a very principal option here but it has lost popularity over the aforementioned alternatives in practice in the last few years. }
4... Be7
{ We enter the classical Queen's Gambit Declined territory but these lines with Bg5 instead of Bf4 are actually not especially dangerous for Black. }
5. Nf3 h6
{ This is considered to be slightly more precise than the immediate  5...O-O  .  Now White has 2 main options and we get very different types of positions in each case. }
6. Bh4 dxc4
{ There are several options here but I like this one for its simplicity. } 7.
e3 { 7.e4?  Nxe4!  and Black wins material, is an important point. } 7... c5 8.
dxc5
{ This move leads to a different kind of position, similar to those analyzed after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p2B1/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  h6  6.Bh4  dxc4  . }
8... Qxd1+ 9. Rxd1 Nbd7
{ Now White has 2 ways to play, go for a symmetrical position with  10.Bxc4  or trying to disrupt Black's structure with  10.c6  . }
10. c6 { 10.Nb5?!  doesn't lead anywhere after the simple  10...O-O =  . }
10... bxc6 11. Bxc4
{ Now White can still hope because at least structurally there is an advantage due to the weak a- and c-pawns.  In reality though, Black has enough time to create a lot of play, mainly using the ...Rb8+...Nd5 combination, the b2-pawn is not easy to defend for White. }
11... Rb8 12. Na4 Nb6 13. Nxb6 Rxb6 14. b3 Bb4+ 15. Ke2
{ This was played in Wang Hao-Anand, Isle of Man 2018. } 15... Nd5 16. a3
{ 16.Rd3  f6  starts to be unpleasant for White as the h4-bishop is out of play, especially after ...e6-e5. }
16... Bxa3 17. Ra1 Bb4 18. Rxa7
{ White takes back the pawn but it's still equal. } 18... Nc3+ 19. Kd3 Nb5
{ Chasing the white rook away from the 7th rank. } 20. Ra8
{ 20.Bxb5  Rxb5=  is also around equal. } 20... O-O 21. Rha1 Nc7 22. R8a7 Nb5
{ The position is equal. } *

