1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ In this chapter, we will take a look at the alternatives to  4.cxd5  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bg5
{ This move is actually the most employed in this position, but it is also true that modern theory considers  4.Nf3  and especially  4.cxd5  to be more challenging for Black.  So we can not really call  4.Bg5  a sideline as it is a very principal option here but it has lost popularity over the aforementioned alternatives in practice in the last few years. }
4... Be7
{ We enter the classical Queen's Gambit Declined territory but these lines with Bg5 instead of Bf4 are actually not especially dangerous for Black. }
5. Nf3 h6
{ This is considered to be slightly more precise than the immediate  5...O-O  .  Now White has 2 main options and we get very different types of positions in each case. }
6. Bh4 dxc4
{ There are several options here but I like this one for its simplicity. } 7.
e3 { 7.e4?  Nxe4!  and Black wins material, is an important point. } 7... c5 8.
Bxc4 cxd4 9. exd4 O-O 10. O-O Nc6
{ This version of the isolated queen pawn is quite comfortable for Black as we will see. }
11. Re1 Nh5
{ Thanks to the inclusion of ...h6 and Bh4, we have this famous resource here which forces simplification and gives Black a good position. }
