[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ In this chapter, we will take a look at the alternatives to  4.cxd5  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bg5
{ This move is actually the most employed in this position, but it is also true that modern theory considers  4.Nf3  and especially  4.cxd5  to be more challenging for Black.  So we can not really call  4.Bg5  a sideline as it is a very principal option here but it has lost popularity over the aforementioned alternatives in practice in the last few years. }
4... Be7
{ We enter the classical Queen's Gambit Declined territory but these lines with Bg5 instead of Bf4 are actually not especially dangerous for Black. }
5. Nf3 h6
{ This is considered to be slightly more precise than the immediate  5...O-O  .  Now White has 2 main options and we get very different types of positions in each case. }
6. Bf4
{ This is the third option here. A little unusual but some strong players employ it from time to time.  White hopes to use the ...h7-h6 move in his favor, mainly with the g2-g4 push at some point. Black should immediately react in the center with ...c7-c5. }
6... O-O 7. e3 c5 8. dxc5 Bxc5
{ We basically get one of the main lines but with the extra move ...h6, which is actually pretty good for Black.  In many of these lines, White uses the attack on h7 as a way to gain tempo @@StartBracket@@Bd3 and Qc2@@EndBracket@@, which now simply doesn't happen.  Also, it's hard to carry out the g2-g4 push with the center open plus the pawn on h6 prevents Bg5 or Ng5 ideas. }
9. cxd5
{ 9.a3  Nc6  10.Qc2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3pp1/4pn1p/2bp4/2P2B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Qc2  Nc6  10.a3  @@StartBracket@@the next variation@@EndBracket@@  . }
9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 Bb4+ 12. Ke2 Nc6
{ ...h6 is very useful for Black in these positions as there is no attack on the h7-pawn. Black is doing more than ok here. For example, }
13. Bc2 Qf6 14. Qd3 g6 15. Bxh6 Re8
{ And White is actually in some trouble here despite the temporary extra pawn. }
*

