[White "13) Other 4th moves: 4.Bg5 (And 4.Bf4)"]
[Black "Other 4th moves: 4.Bg5 Be7 5.Nf3 h6 6.Bxf6 #8/17"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ In this chapter, we will take a look at the alternatives to  4.cxd5  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bg5
{ This move is actually the most employed in this position, but it is also true that modern theory considers  4.Nf3  and especially  4.cxd5  to be more challenging for Black.  So we can not really call  4.Bg5  a sideline as it is a very principal option here but it has lost popularity over the aforementioned alternatives in practice in the last few years. }
4... Be7
{ We enter the classical Queen's Gambit Declined territory but these lines with Bg5 instead of Bf4 are actually not especially dangerous for Black. }
5. Nf3 h6
{ This is considered to be slightly more precise than the immediate  5...O-O  .  Now White has 2 main options and we get very different types of positions in each case. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6
{ This is also a big tabiya of the QGD but it is actually quite solid and good for Black and it has been considered to be so for several years by now.  In general Black's main idea is to take on c4 and then use either the ...c7-c5 or ...e6-e5 break to completely solve the opening problems.  There is a huge body of theory here but I will present to you what I think is vital to know when playing Black. }
7. e3
{ 7.Rc1  O-O  8.e3  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  O-O  8.Rc1  . }
7... O-O 8. Qc2 c5 9. dxc5 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nd7 11. c6
{ Since Black is going to regain the pawn anyway, White tries to at least create some weaknesses in Black's camp but it turns out that Black doesn't even need to take it.   11.Ne4  Nxc5! =  .   11.O-O  Nxc5  12.Rfd1  Qe7=  Black is doing well here. }
11... Ne5
{ Simply taking on c6 is also fine but this gives Black quite nice compensation. }
12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. f4
{ 13.cxb7?!  Bxb7  gives Black too much initiative, White is in fact worse after  14.O-O  Qc7  . }
13... Bf6 14. Ne4 Be7
{ Is also excellent for Black with Qb6 next move and every time White takes on b7 there will be a huge compensation after the bishop recaptures. }
*

