[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Tigran Petrosian − Robert James Fischer, Candidates, Buenos Aires 1971"]
[Result "*"]

{ Even the great Bobby Fischer was attracted to the soundness of the Semi-Tarrasch, he employed it quite often and even in important matches like this one. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3
{ As we said previously in the course, this move was very popular in those times. }
5... Nc6
{ This is not the move I recommend in the course but obviously, a very logical one.   5...a6  is the move we intend to play ourselves. }
6. a3
{ 6.cxd5  is also a very principled line and if Black takes with the pawn then 7.Bb5. }
6... Ne4
{ An interesting move.   6...a6  Is again a very sound alternative and actually the main move according to theory. }
7. Qc2 Nxc3 8. bxc3 Be7 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Bd3 h6
{ Black's play is remarkably simple and his position is quite comfortable already. }
11. O-O Na5 12. Nd2
{ Trying to keep the tension in the center.   12.cxd5  exd5  13.dxc5  Bxc5  was also fine for Black, the bishop on b2 is passive and in case of  14.c4  Nxc4  15.Bxc4  dxc4  16.Qxc4  Qe7  Black has the bishop pair and a small advantage. }
12... dxc4 13. Nxc4 Nxc4 14. Bxc4 b6
{ A typical way of developing the bishop. Black intends ...Bb7 and ...Rc8. }
15. e4
{ White will try to use his central majority, so now we have the typical clash between Black's play on the queenside and along the c-file with White's central pawns and prospects of a central break  @@StartBracket@@d4-d5 most likely@@EndBracket@@ and a potential attack on the kingside.  Here the somewhat simplified nature of the position plays in Black's favor. Fischer's way of handling the middlegame is anyway exemplary. }
15... Bb7 16. Qe2 { Anticipating the black rook coming to c8. } 16... Rc8 17.
Bb3
{ Understandably, Petrosian wants to step out of any ...cxd4 and ...Bxe4 tactics, but now Fischer starts to put his queenside into motion in order to enhance the counterplay. }
17... b5
{ A nice move, typical by the way of these structures @@StartBracket@@we saw it often in the main lines@@EndBracket@@ Black gives space for the queen to come to b6. }
18. f4
{ 18.Qxb5?  Bxe4∓  As usual this exchange is in Black's favor as the central pawn is more important. Also, White's pieces are badly placed and vulnerable on the b-file. }
18... Qb6 19. Kh1
{ In case of  19.f5?  Black would play  19...c4  20.Bc2  e5-+  when Black's position is just winning. }
19... cxd4 20. cxd4 b4
{ Again, we see how fast and effective Black's play on the queenside really is. Now ...Ba6 is a huge threat. }
21. axb4 Bxb4 22. d5
{ Finally White was able to carry out the typical break in order to open the bishops, but Black is just in time with his counterplay. }
22... Bc3
{ Getting rid of the dangerous white bishop, now it's clear that White is some trouble and has to be very careful. }
23. Bxc3 Rxc3 24. Bc2
{ Under huge pressure Petrosian makes a decisive mistake.   24.Ba2  was correct when Black is a bit better but White should survive. }
24... exd5 25. e5
{ There is just no compensation for the pawn. This type of pawn sac is possible often, as we have seen before, but here Black's pieces are just too active. }
25... Re3 26. Qd2 d4
{ Opening the bishop and also advancing the passed pawn. The rook on e3 is also doing a great job. Black is winning and Fischer brought it home without too many problems. }
27. Rab1 Qa6 28. Rf2 Rd8 29. Kg1 Be4 30. Bxe4 Rxe4 31. h3 d3 32. Rb3 Qc4 33.
Rb2 Rdd4 34. g3 Rd5 35. Kh2 Rb5 36. Ra2 Rb1
{ Finally going for the white king. There is nothing to do for White anymore. }
37. g4 Re2 38. Rxe2 dxe2 39. Qxe2 Qxf4+ 40. Kg2 Rb3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Shakhriyar Mamedyarov − Ding Liren, Candidates, Berlin 2018"]
[Result "*"]

{ The Chinese GM is one of the main defenders of the Semi-Tarrasch at the highest level. This game is one of his best efforts. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rad1 Bb7 14.
Rfe1 Rc8 15. Bb3 Re8 16. h3 Nf6
{ The main move in this position and as I said in the theory section, a very sound one.   Nevertheless, my recommendation is the fresh and interesting  16...Qf6  . }
17. Qf4 Nh5
{ Black is forcing the white queen to a very passive square in order to avoid repetition. }
18. Qh2
{ 18.Qe3  Nf6  and it's hard to protect e4 without repeating moves.   18.Qe5  Nf6  also leads nowhere for White. The queen is not well placed on e5. }
18... h6
{ The typical waiting, useful move is very appropriate here.   18...Nf6?  would be bad due to  19.d5  exd5  20.e5±  and since ...Ne4 is not possible, Black is in trouble. }
19. Ne5
{ 19.d5  is also possible here but not as deadly as with the black knight on f6.  19...exd5  20.e5  g6  This position is one of the critical ones for the assessment of the whole 16...Nf6 and ...Nh5 line. Obviously, White has compensation but I think objectively Black is doing well. }
19... Nf6 20. Qf4 b5
{ We see again this typical resource. Black clears b6 for the queen and also prepares ...a5-a4. }
21. Re3 Rc7
{ Good prophylaxis against Rg3. Black would have ...Nh5 and f7 is protected. }
22. Nd3
{ Logical, trying to exploit the weakened c5-square but it won't be such a big deal for Black, now Black gets to trade a pair of rooks which is positionally very desirable.   After the thematic advance  22.d5  exd5  23.exd5  Qd6  Black has a good position. }
22... Rc3
{ Now it's hard for White to escape the rook trade, so he should continue with his plan. }
23. Nc5 Rxe3 24. Qxe3 Bc6
{ Despite the nice-looking knight on c5, Black has a very decent position. The plan with ...a5-a4 is still very much on Black's agenda. }
25. Rc1 Qb6 26. f3 Rd8
{ Improving the rook and keeping an eye on the d4-pawn seems very natural. }
27. Kf2 a5 28. g4
{ In a way natural because it seems vaguely possible that White will get some kind of attack with g5 and so on but in reality, he won't have time for that, so this creates some weaknesses. It was better to play more solidly.   28.a3  And although Black is doing well, maybe the position is just very equal.   28.Nxe6  was one of the possibilities according to the machine but after  28...fxe6  29.Bxe6+  Kf8  30.d5  Qxe3+  31.Kxe3  Bd7  Black is in no way worse in this endgame. }
28... a4 29. Bc2 Nd7
{ A good move, getting finally rid of the knight. White is under some pressure now. }
30. Bd3
{ After this it gets easier for Black as he has a very clear plan of advancing the pawns.   30.Nd3  was correct when White is still keeping his position under control. }
30... Nxc5 31. Rxc5 b4 32. Bc4 Bd7
{ Getting the bishop out and also preparing, for example, ...Rc8. } 33. g5 hxg5
34. Qxg5 Be8 35. Qe7 b3 { White has no way to stop the pawns now. } 36. axb3 a3
{ 36...axb3  37.Bxb3  was not necessary, since the pawn advance to a3 is just winning. }
37. b4 Ra8 38. d5 { Desperation.   38.Ba2  Qxb4  was also hopeless. } 38... a2
{ Ding correctly calculates that he can just queen the pawn and White has no mate on the kingside. }
39. dxe6 a1=Q 40. exf7+ Bxf7 41. Bxf7+ Kh7
{ The c5-rook in pinned so there is no Rh5. There is only one last hope... }
42. Qh4+ Qh6 43. Rh5
{ It looks like White might still be in the game but Ding had clearly seen all this when he went for 38...a2. }
43... Qa7+ { This is important. White loses his bishop so he resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Hikaru Nakamura − Leinier Dominguez, PRO Chess League, chess.com 2018"]
[Result "*"]

{ I am happy to present to you one of my own games. I had just started to employ the Semi-Tarrasch at this point. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Be2 { A rather modest continuation. }
11... b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Qe3 Nc6
{ When we can make sure that d4-d5 is totally under control, the development of the knight on c6 is a bit more active as it puts pressure on d4. }
14. Rfd1 Qd6
{ This is a very typical move in these positions. Now in case of d5, after the pawn trade in the center, the remaining passed pawn would be safely blockaded. The move also makes room for ...Rfd8. }
15. e5
{ A very commital move, now Black has a clear plan of re-routing his knight to e7 in order to control the weakened squares.   15.d5  exd5  16.exd5?  Ne7∓  and Black is just better. }
15... Qd5 16. Ne1 Ne7
{ A typical move in positions where White plays e4-e5. We transfer the knight to e7 where it will be flexible and ready to go to d5, f5 or g6. }
17. h4 h6
{ Another typically useful move, creating luft and also taking g5 under control just in case. White's position is already very difficult. }
18. Bd3 Rac8 19. Qe2 Nc6
{ Not the best but luckily it doesn't spoil much.   19...Rc3!  was much stronger when Black is totally dominating. }
20. Qe4 Qxe4 21. Bxe4 Rfd8
{ The endgame is still very unpleasant for White. Black's pieces are excellently placed and White's pawns are rather weak. }
22. f4 Ba8 { Getting ready to re-route the knight once again! } 23. Nf3 Nb4 24.
Bxa8 Rxa8
{ The position is close to losing for White, it's mainly because White's pawns are so weak that they are almost impossible to defend. }
25. a3 Nc2 26. Ra2 Ne3 { 26...Rac8  was very strong as well. } 27. Rb1
{ 27.Rd3  Nd5  28.g3  was better, although after  28...Rac8  White's position remains difficult. }
27... Nd5 { Now White loses material. } 28. Rb3 Nxf4
{ Winning a pawn while keeping all the positional advantage. Hikaru kept on fighting since this was a rapid game. }
29. a4 Rac8 30. a5 Nd5 31. axb6 axb6 32. Kh2 Rc7 33. Rbb2 Rdc8 34. h5 b5
{ With this little tactic, the pawn gets to b4. } 35. Nd2
{ 35.Rxb5  Nc3  is obviously the point. } 35... b4 36. Ra1 Rc2 37. Rba2 Nf4 38.
Nb3 Nxh5
{ Winning a second pawn. The rest doesn't really require much commentary. } 39.
Nc5 Rxa2 40. Rxa2 Nf4 41. Rb2 Nd5 42. Ra2 Rb8 43. Nb3 h5 44. Ra7 g5 45. Kg1 Kg7
46. Kf2 Kg6 47. Kf3 g4+ 48. Kg3 Ne3 49. Kf2 Nf5 50. Ra6 Rd8 51. Rb6 Nxd4 52.
Rd6 Rxd6 53. exd6 Nc6 54. d7 Kf6
{ This game shows how easy it can be for Black to take over the initiative in these positions. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ian Nepomniachtchi − Wesley So, FTX Crypto Cup, chess24.com 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ Wesley also occasionally plays the Semi-Tarrasch with success. This game, even though an online rapid one, contains some very interesting ideas that I think are useful for us to study. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5
{ This is the starting position of another big line in the Semi-Tarrasch. I believe this particular one, especially the move  7.Rb1  here, is the most dangerous for Black.  Black does not get to trade bishops with ...cxd4 and ...Bb4+ which means that White's space advantage and central pawn majority could play a more important role as there are more pieces on the board, but, as I am going to demonstrate, Black's position is perfectly sound and very playable at all levels. }
7. Rb1
{ Now we come to the best move for White in this position. White stops ...Bb4+ and, besides doing so, he also activates the rook. }
7... Be7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. h4 { Nepo goes for one of the most critical lines. }
9... b6
{ An interesting line that is actually what we intend to play. Black prepares ...Bb7. }
10. h5 h6
{ In general, I think Black should refrain from allowing h5-h6 in these positions as that would create long-term problems for our king. }
11. Bd3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nc6
{ Here we intend to play 12...e5 which I believe is better, but the move of So is also possible.   12...e5!  is the move I recommend in the theory section. }
13. Be2
{ I don't like this way of defending d4.   13.Be3  seems more natural to me, not only defending the central pawn but also preparing Qd2 and Bxh6, for example,  13...Bb7  14.Qd2  Qd6  15.O-O  Rfd8  16.Rb3!  Another typical resource for White in these positions. The rook might be transferred to g3 quite soon and also b1 is cleared for the bishop. White has a nice initiative here. }
13... Bb7 14. Rh3 Rc8 { Now Black's position seems quite satisfactory. } 15.
Rg3 Kh8 16. a3
{ Preventing ...Nb4 but now Black finds another route for the knight. } 16...
Na5 17. Bd3
{ 17.d5  was possibly better and after  17...exd5  18.Qd4!  This move is hard to see.   18.Bb2  seems more natural but then Black plays  18...Bf6  19.e5  Bh4  20.Rg4  Be7  with a good position since after  21.e6  there is always  21...Bf6∓  .  18...f6  now it's not good to play   18...Bf6?  because  19.e5  Be7  20.Qg4  Rg8  21.Bb2+-  is just crushing.  Even after the scary-looking  19.Nh4  Black is actually quite safe , for example  19...Rf7  20.Ng6+  Kg8  and Black is doing quite well, it's probably objectively around equal. }
17... Nc4 18. Kf1 { 18.Qe2?  Nxa3  would be just winning for Black. } 18... Nd6
{ The knight changes position. The main point is to counter-attack with the ...f7-f5 break.  The immediate   18...f5!?  was also possible. }
19. d5
{ This typical push just doesn't work for White here.   19.Qe2  had to be played, although after  19...f5!  20.exf5  Nxf5⇆  which was the main point of ...Nd6, Black has very nice play. }
19... exd5 20. Bb2 dxe4
{ It turns out that Bg7 is just a check and after that White is losing material. }
21. Bxg7+ { 21.Rxg7  Bf6-+  . } 21... Kh7 22. Bxf8 Bxf8 23. Rg4
{ 23.Bc2  Nf5-+  was also a nice point. After ...Qd8 Black takes the rook with check first and wins. }
23... exd3 24. Rd4 Rc3
{ White is dead lost. The game lasted another 15 moves but the evaluation never changed. }
25. Qd2 Qc7 26. Qf4 Bxf3 27. gxf3 Rc4 28. Rd1 Rxd4 29. Qxd4 Qc4 30. Qe3 Nb5 31.
Rxd3 Bxa3 32. Kg2 Bc5 33. Qd2 Nd4 34. Re3 a5 35. Re5 f6 36. Re4 f5 37. Re8 Qf7
38. Qe1 Qg7+ 39. Kh1 Nxf3 40. Qd1 Qf7 { And finally White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Hrant Melkumyan − Andrei Volokitin, Austrian Bundesliga 2016/2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 6. d4 cxd4 7. exd4 Nxc3 8.
bxc3 Qc7
{ After a different move order in the opening, the game transposes to one of our main lines in the theory section. This game is actually quite instructive when studying positions with hanging pawns. }
9. Bd2 Nd7 10. Bd3 b6
{ As we discussed in the theory section, I prefer to start with  10...Bd6  here. }
11. O-O
{ 11.Ng5!?  is interesting for White in this move order and that's the reason I find 10...Bd6 simpler. }
11... Bd6 { Now the game transposes back to our lines. } 12. Re1 Bb7 13. c4 O-O
14. h3 Bf4
{ In the theory section, I recommend  14...Rfe8  which is slightly more flexible. That said, there is nothing wrong with the move played and in fact I chose this game because the way Volokitin handles the middle game is worthy of a model game. }
15. Bc3
{ Of course, the trade would benefit Black because White loses the potential for dynamic, active play and that would allow Black to calmly increase the pressure over the hanging pawns. }
15... Rac8 16. Qe2
{ This move seems normal but in fact, it allows Black to immediately put pressure on the pawns and force some trades.   I would prefer  16.Bb2  , getting the bishop out of the c-file and setting a little trap:  16...Ba6?!   16...Rfd8  would be correct, with a complex and probably objectively balanced position.  17.d5!  This is the move that White is always looking for in this structure, it works quite well here, for example,  17...exd5  18.cxd5  Bxd3  19.Qxd3  White is already much better as  19...Qc2  fails to  20.Qd4  Nf6  21.Qxf4  Qxb2  22.d6±  With a huge advantage for White. }
16... Ba6
{ Now in order to protect the pawn on c4 White has to trade some minor pieces, which, as we said many times already, favor Black in this structure. }
17. Bd2 Bxd2 18. Nxd2 Rfd8
{ The computer still evaluates this as 0.00 and it's probably right objectively, as usual, but I believe that from the practical point of view, it's way easier to play with Black here because White just lacks active ideas and the pawns are constantly under some pressure. }
19. Rac1 Nf6 20. Nb3
{ Given the pawn on b6 this knight has little future here   20.Qe3  was better and after  20...Qd7  21.Nf3  Bb7  22.Red1  Bxf3  23.Qxf3  Qa4  the computer is still not very impressed and thinks White has no problems, although it seems to me that Black has some annoying pressure. }
20... Qd7
{ Eyeing the a4-square which is one of the weaknesses in White's camp. } 21.
Rc2 Rc7
{ Another typical way to increase the pressure. ...Rdc8 is the obvious intention }
22. Rec1 h6
{ Black has no rush, White can't do much to change the character of the position, that's why I think is so unpleasant to be White here. }
23. Rc3 Rdc8 24. Qb2 Bb7 { Looking for new prospects on the long diagonal. }
25. f3
{ A very ugly move, weakening the king and a whole complex of squares around it. It would appear that White wants to place his queen on f2 but it still looks very unnecessary.   It was probably better to just wait with a move like  25.R3c2  or something similar. }
25... Bc6
{ Preparing ...Ba4 possibly and switching the attack to the d4 pawn with ...Rd8 and so on. }
26. R3c2 Qd6 27. Bf1 Qg3 28. Rc3 Ba4
{ Black plays in both flanks, his position is so dominant that he can do almost whatever he wants. That said, he still needs to find a way to make progress. }
29. Nd2 Qf4 30. Rd3 Rd8
{ The d4-pawn starts to suffer now. Also, the beauty of a move like ...Rc7 in these positions is that it's incredibly easy for Black to switch between attacks in both the c- and the d-file. }
31. Re1 Rcd7 32. Ne4 Nxe4
{ A mistake that greatly reduces Black's advantage.   32...Bc6∓  was the right way to play keeping a clear plus. }
33. Rxe4
{ White could have taken the opportunity to change the pawn structure with  33.fxe4!  and Black's advantage almost completely disappears. }
33... Qf6
{ Now Black is again better although his advantage is less significant than before as it's not so simple to make progress. }
34. Qd2 Bc6 35. Re5 h5
{ Trying to improve the structure on the kingside and fix the white pawns. }
36. f4 { 36.Rxh5?  Rxd4  is obviously a bad trade for White. } 36... h4 37. Qe3
{ A step in the wrong direction.   37.d5  was better:  37...exd5  38.cxd5  Bb5  39.Rd4  Bxf1  40.Kxf1=  and it's clear that White is past the worst. }
37... g6
{ Since White can't do much Black decides to improve the position of his king. The next phase of the game is played with great technique by Volokitin. }
38. Kh2 Kg7 39. Be2 Rd6
{ Black keeps improving his position little by little, now ...R8d7 and ...Qd8 become possible. }
40. Bf1
{ Probably in time pressure @@StartBracket@@move 40th@@EndBracket@@ White overlooks Black's idea.   40.Bd1  was better and although his position is still a bit unpleasant, White seems to keep the balance.  40...R8d7  41.Bb3  Qd8  42.d5  being the main point. }
40... R8d7 { Now White is in big trouble once again. } 41. Kg1 Bb7
{ Good prophylaxis against a possible d4-d5 hitting the bishop. White has not many moves anyway.   The immediate  41...Qd8  would allow  42.f5  gxf5  43.d5  and White is able to create some confusion. }
42. a4 Qd8 43. d5
{ The final mistake, after which White won't have more chances.   43.f5!  was the only way to stay in the game:  43...exf5  44.d5  Qf6  and Black is much better but White keeps some chances. }
43... exd5 44. cxd5 Ba6
{ Good enough, but there was an equally strong alternative:  44...Bxd5  45.f5  Qf6!  46.fxg6  Bc4-+  Black's last two moves are not so simple to spot at the board, so the way Volokitin played is practically understandable. }
45. Rd1 Bxf1 46. Rxf1 Rxd5 47. f5 Rd1
{ After the exchange of the f1-rook, White's king will be very vulnerable } 48.
Re8 Qf6 49. Qe5 Qxe5 50. Rxe5 Kf6 51. Rb5 g5
{ The f5-pawn is doomed, the rest is very easy. } 52. a5 R1d5 53. Rfb1 bxa5 54.
Kf2 Kxf5 55. Rxd5+ Rxd5 56. Rb7 Ke4 57. Rxa7 f5 58. g3 hxg3+ 59. Kxg3 Rd3+ 60.
Kg2 Rd2+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Yaroslav Zherebukh − Aleksandr Shimanov, PRO Chess League, chess.com 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. d4 d5 4. Nc3 c5
{ Once again, after a little different order of moves, the game is back to the main Semi-Tarrasch position. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 cxd4 7. exd4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 Qc7 9. Bd2 Nd7 10. Bd3 b6
{ 10...Bd6  is our move. } 11. O-O
{ 11.Ng5!?  is interesting for White here as I mentioned in the previous game. }
11... Bb7 12. Re1 Bd6 13. h4
{ A dubious plan that doesn't create any problems for Black. } 13... O-O 14. h5
h6 15. Qe2
{ 15.Qc1  is met by  15...Bxf3  16.gxf3  Rac8  when Black is much better as  17.Bxh6  Qxc3∓  doesn't work for White. }
15... Bf4
{ Again we see this typical maneuver, with the bishop trade White loses attacking potential. }
16. Ne5 Nxe5
{ 16...Bxe5!?  was also strong, for example  17.dxe5  Rfd8  18.Bf4  Nf6!  Black has other ways but this is especially strong, the white queen is denied access to g4 and Black has multiple threats now, like ...Nxh5 or ...Qc6  19.Rad1  Qc6  20.Qf1  Nd5∓  . }
17. Bxf4 Qc6 { A typical intermezzo. } 18. f3 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Rac8 20. Bd2 Rfd8
{ White's pawns are very weak. Black is not only much better but also his moves are all very natural. }
21. a4 Rd5 22. Re5 Rxe5
{ Black decides to transpose to an endgame.   The middlegame with  22...Qc7  23.Rxd5  Bxd5∓  was also pretty sad for White. }
23. dxe5 Qc5+ 24. Qd4 Qxd4+ 25. cxd4 Rc2 26. Be3
{ The bishop is too passive here, especially after Black's next move.   26.Bb4  was a bit better intending at least Bd6-Bb8. }
26... Bd5 27. a5
{ The last mistake, although now it was hard to at least keep the game going.   27.Rc1  Ra2  28.Rc8+  Kh7  29.Rc7  Rxa4  30.Rxf7  b5-+  is also hopeless. }
27... b5 { Now the b-pawn is too strong and it's just very easy for Black. }
28. Rc1 Ra2 29. Rc8+ Kh7 30. Rb8 Rxa5 31. Bd2 Ra2 32. Be1 a6 33. Kf1 a5 34. Kg1
b4 35. Rb5 b3 { And White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Sarin Nihal − Fabiano Caruana, FIDE Grand Swiss, Riga 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played relatively recently in the Grand Swiss tournament in Riga. I think the first part of the game  (the first 25 moves)  was played in an exemplary fashion by Caruana. That's the reason I decided to include only that first part.  It should serve us as a good model for these kinds of positions with IQP. Especially when we analyze and also discover what are the best ideas and setups for White as well. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 { 3...Nf6  would be our move here. } 4. e3 Nf6 5.
Nf3 { Now we are back in the 5.e3 line. } 5... a6
{ This is actually our own move in the course. } 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Be2 Nc6 8. O-O
Bd6 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b3
{ This is a very logical move of course, but as we discussed in the theory section, I consider  10.a3  followed by b4 to be more challenging for Black. }
10... O-O 11. Bb2 Ba7 12. Rc1 Re8
{ This is perfectly normal but our recommendation in the course is actually  12...Bf5  and if  13.h3  @@StartBracket@@like Nihal played@@EndBracket@@ then we play  13...Bg6  and meet  14.Bd3  with  14...Bh5  .   12...d4?!  might seem good but doesn't really equalize after  13.exd4  Nxd4  14.Nxd4  Bxd4  15.Bf3⩲  White keeps a significant advantage due to his development advantage. }
13. h3
{ A good move, the point of which is to play Be2-d3 and Nc3-e2 eliminating the possibility of Bg4. The Bd3, Ne2 setup is quite desirable for White in these positions as it firmly controls d4 and also opens the b2-bishop and gives the additional possibility of Nf4 which could be unpleasant for Black. }
13... Qd6
{ 13...d4?!  14.exd4  Nxd4  15.Nxd4  Bxd4  16.Bf3⩲  is still unpleasant for Black.   13...Bf5  14.Bd3  Ne4  15.Ne2  offers White some hopes of an advantage as well. }
14. Bd3 Bd7
{ Fabiano decides to complete his development first which makes a lot of sense. }
15. Ne2 Rad8
{ This seems like a critical moment, White needs to be precise if he wants to keep chances of an advantage. }
16. Ned4
{ Natural but in a way too commital. It seems better @@StartBracket@@as usual in such situations@@EndBracket@@ to keep the flexibility in terms of which piece to put on d4. Plus the knight could eventually be more effective in another square, like f4 for example.   16.Re1!?  was interesting  16...Bb8   16...Ne4  17.Bxe4  Rxe4  18.Qd3⩲  17.Nf4  Ne4  18.Nh5  f6  19.Nf4⩲  After provoking the move ...f6, White keeps some advantage.   16.Bb1!?  also makes sense, keeping flexibility. Now  16...Bb8?  Would actually put Black in serious trouble after   16...Ne4  17.Bxe4  Rxe4  is better when White's advantage is only minimal.  17.Nf4±  With moves like Qd3 and Rfd1 to follow. We see that the knight is actually more effective on f4 than on d4. }
16... Ne4
{ Now Black is immediately fine. It was crucial for White to meet this move with Bxe4 forcing Black to recapture with the rook. Now he simply takes ...dxe4. }
17. Qe2
{ Preparing Rfd1 but Nihal should have sensed the danger.   17.Bxe4  dxe4  18.Nxc6  Bxc6  19.Qxd6  Rxd6  20.Nd4  was a way to bail out and, the position is dead equal. }
17... Bb8
{ Now White is in trouble, the knight is pretty on d4 but it doesn't cause Black any problems. }
18. Rfd1 Qg6 19. Nh4
{ Another mistake, this time more serious. Maybe he simply overlooked Black's sequence.   19.Nxc6  had to be played and after  19...bxc6  20.Bxe4  dxe4  21.Ne1  White is worse but keeps chances. }
19... Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Qh6 21. Nf3 Bxh3 22. gxh3 Qxh3
{ Black has multiple threats, ...Rd6, ...Ng5 and so on. White has no choice but to give back a piece. }
23. Qf1 Qxf3 24. Qg2 Qxg2+ 25. Kxg2
{ Black was up two pawns with a winning position. Strangely enough, the game was a draw later on move 54. }
*

